<HEADLINE> 3 British Tomb Robbers Sentenced in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 16 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian Higher State
Security Court today sentenced three people, including a Briton to
15 years in prison for stealing and smuggling Egyptian antiquities
abroad.
</P>
<P>
Six others involved in the case received ten year imprisonment
terms. Two of them are Britons.
</P>
<P>
Jonathan Tokeley-Parry, an art restorer from Devon, southeast
Britain, was convicted on charges of robbing Egyptian
archaeological sites and smuggling precious antiques disguised as
cheap artifacts out of Egypt as part of an international
trafficking network.
</P>
<P>
The Englishman, who is to serve the longest prison term among
the other Britons in the case, was also charged with tampering
with Egypt's archeological heritage in 1992 and 1993 at the
Saqqara necropolis near Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The stolen pieces included stones from the entrances of tombs
and a statue of the god Horus, who was half-man, half-falcon.
</P>
<P>
Tokeley-Parry had made off with the objects with the help of an
accomplice who traveled to Egypt six times between June 1992 and
December 1993, Egypt's MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The court condemned three more to serve five years in prison
and acquited another three. 
</P>
</TEXT>
