<HEADLINE> Great Efforts Required to Solve Problems: Khalid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's caretaker Prime
Minister Meraj Khalid said today that great efforts were still
required to solve major problems facing the country despite
measures taken by his government to straighten the socio-economic
fabric.
</P>
<P>
Khalid said in his farewell address to the nation that the
nation has to "go a long way to surmount the multitude of varied
problems facing it through selfless and upright approach and
conduct."
</P>
<P>
It was a happy augury, he said, that both, the electorate and
the newly-elected public representatives, were fully conversant
with the actual problems and were determined to see rapid uplift
of the society.
</P>
<P>
Khalid said that common hind-sighted attitudes and indulgence
in petty interests as well as the prevalent evils of parochialism,
sectarianism and rampant corruption have of late eaten up the
vital elements of the nation.
</P>
<P>
Without cohesion and national integrity, political stability
could not be achieved, the caretaker Prime Minister said.
</P>
<P>
Khalid gave a detailed account of the accomplishments made by
the caretaker set-up during its three-month tenure.
</P>
<P>
The recent general elections, he said, have made it amply clear
that the masses are wide awake of their requirements and
aspirations and the verdict given by them adequately demonstrates
it.
</P>
<P>
He said it was imperative upon the political leadership to
adhere to the necessary trait of self-accountability and see to it
that accountability remained a constant feature in the national
life, so that the plundered money is positively returned to the
national exchequer.
</P>
<P>
He believed that a new political culture is emerging "in which
the political leadership today finds itself intricately involved
and affiliated".
</P>
<P>
Khalid said, "It is a matter of satisfaction that we have
fulfilled the duty bestowed upon us to hold free, fair and
impartial election."
</P>
<P>
The observers from all over the world have termed the electoral
process transparent, impartial and peaceful, he added.
</P>
<P>
The caretaker government, Khalid said, had presented a
comprehensive accountability ordinance and initiated collection of
evidence against the corrupt.
</P>
<P>
A gigantic task before the caretakers, he said, "was to counter
the economic collapse of the country and save it from being
declared a defaulter which could have led to serious consequences
for Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
There was no option left but to seek cooperation of
international financial institutions to avert the situation, he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
