<HEADLINE> U.S. Orders Indian Diplomats to Leave in Retaliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
ordered two Indian diplomats to leave the country as a retaliation
to expulsion of two American officials from New Dehli last month,
a State Department spokesman said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Glyn Davies said the two Indian consulates, stationed
in San Francisco and Chigago, were ordered the expulsion on Feb.
10 for "activities that were incompatible with their consular
status."
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Press Trust of India said one of the Americans
ordered to leave India reportedly had "unauthorized" links with a
man called Rattan Sehgal, identified as a director in charge of
the anti-espionage division of India's Intelligence Bureau. The
American was the station chief of the CIA in New Dehli. 
</P>
</TEXT>
