<HEADLINE> Egypt Qualifies for Japanese Soft Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Japan has notified Egypt that
its successful economic reforms have made it qualified to ask for
Japanese easy-term loans, the Egyptian Middle East News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
It said that this was expressed today during a meeting between
Egyptian Minister of Economy and International Cooperation Nawal
al-Tatawi and a visiting delegation of the Japanese Overseas
Cooperation Fund.
</P>
<P>
Under a soft loan arrangement which is regarded as a
preferential treatment, the beneficiary is allowed to make the
loan payment with its local currency instead of hard currency.
</P>
<P>
Tatawi welcomed the Japanese announcement, saying that this
would increase Egypt's chances to diversify its sources of
financing to fund government and private investments.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that now the Egyptian private sector and
banks would finance the biggest part of the country's vast growing
investments in all fields, especially in the New Delta and in
Sinai.
</P>
<P>
However, Egypt would still be in need of more financing through
soft loans from donor countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
The international assistance to Egypt amounts to 8 billion
U.S. dollars every year. The United States, Germany, France,
Japan, Britain, Italy, Belgium, the Netherlands, the World Bank
and the International Monetary Fund are its major donors.
</P>
</TEXT>
