<HEADLINE> UK Government Confident of Victory in BSE Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 16 (Xinhua) -- The British Conservative
government said Sunday that it is confident of victory in Monday's
Labor-inspired censure vote on its handling of the BSE or mad cow
crisis, according to reports here today.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Labor Party has earlier called for a vote in the
lower House of Commons on Monday on whether to censure the
Agriculture Minister Douglas Hogg for his handling of the mad cow
disease crisis.
</P>
<P>
If the government was defeated in the vote, it could mean a
full vote of confidence in the government and an early general
election.
</P>
<P>
Welsh Secretary William Hague, speaking on BBC television,
called Labor's censure motion "a bit of a desperate tactic".
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Labor leader Tony Blair admitted that the government
is likely to "scrape through" the vote and that the Labor Party is
unlikely to be able to bring down the government and force an
early election.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Conservative Party now has 323 MPs, the same number
as the combined vote of the opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that strenuous efforts are being made to ensure
the presence of every Tory MP for Monday's vote, with Foreign
Secretary Malcolm Rifkind cutting short a visit to Hong Kong in
order to attend.
</P>
<P>
A Labor spokesman said he believed that the nine Ulster
Unionist MPs would not vote against the government, saying that
they were likely to either abstain or back Hogg.
</P>
<P>
The minority Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown said that
the government is likely to win Monday's BSE censure vote because
of Labor clumsiness.
</P>
<P>
He told Sky News that Labor's failure to consult other parties
was likely to mean victory for the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
