<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-16 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Defense Minister Voices Satisfaction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai today expressed satisfaction with the situation
in Hebron after Israeli troop pullback last month.
</P>
<P>
During a tour of the Hebron area that remains under Israeli
control, Mordechai met with Palestinian residents and Jewish
settlers. He said basically there was no violation of the Hebron
agreement by the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
"The situation now is quiet, both sides give respect to each
other and they hope the situation in Hebron will continue like
as now," Mordechai told reporters.
</P>
<P>
But the minister had a sharp exchange with settler leaders in
a short but stormy meeting. The settlers lodged a complain about
the discrimination against them, which was rejected by
Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
The minister ruled out of any deviation from the signed
Hebron agreement, saying Israel would proceed with the plans of
reopening the Shuhada street and the vegetable market in the city
center.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Jewish settlers from the Avraham Avinu
settlement and Palestinian residents exchanged abuses and threw
vegetables at each other in a dispute over the reopening of the
vegetable market. Israel allowed the reopening of the market in
accordance with the Hebron agreement signed last month.
</P>
<P>
No one was injured and no damage caused in the clash as
Israeli police and troops quickly separated and dispersed the
crowd before the confrontation turned violent.
</P>
<P>
The settlers claimed that the reopening of the vegetable
market, closed since the 1994 massacre in which a Jewish
extremist killed 29 Palestinian worshipers in a nearby Mosque,
could expose them to more Palestinian violence.
</P>
<P>
The settlers also complained that the civil administration in
Hebron had not permitted them to build new houses in the Jewish
settlements while Palestinian residents were allowed to do
so.
</P>
<P>
Noam Arnon, the spokesman for Hebron settlers, condemned the
discrimination against them. "The discrimination against Jews
living in Hebron is going on. As we understand, in the
Palestinian side, projects are initialed and built, but in the
Jewish quarter, even no one house is now permitted," he said
angrily.
</P>
<P>
He said that the settlers would consider new steps to wedge a
campaign against the government. "We have to consider our steps
from now on. We are going to open a campaign around this
problem," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
