<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Institute Warns of Recession in Eastern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Eastern German economy might slip
into recession in 1997 if Bonn fails to provide sufficient
financial support to the eastern states, the German Institute for
Economic Research (DIW) in Berlin warned today.
</P>
<P>
Bonn government had spent billions of marks mainly to stimulate
the building sector in eastern Germany. At the moment most of the
money is running out, "but the baton change to the other
industries do not work," said DIW president Lutz Hoffmann in an
interview with the Welt am Sonntag newspaper.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that Bonn annually provided the eastern part of
the country with about 92 billion U.S. dollars in support funds
over recent years.
</P>
<P>
However, the economic upturn in the east lost impetus in 1996
in the wake of the slowdown in the building sector. Many east
German firms had difficulties competing on markets both at home
and abroad.
</P>
<P>
According to Hoffmann's estimates, the public investments in
eastern Germany must be at least increased by 20 billion marks
(about 12 billion U.S. dollars) in next year.
</P>
<P>
"The East needs at least as much as money as so far in the next
few years. The government support cannot be cut in any case,"
Hoffmann said, adding that such a support is needed for at least
ten years in eastern Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
