<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Extends Deadline on Turning in Illegal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Iran's prosecutor general has
once again extended the deadline on turning in weapons for those
who missed an earlier deadline on October 13, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Qadiriyan, an official from the Prosecutor General
Office, said today that those who were not able to hand in their
weapons by the last deadline have to turn in their weapons before
August 16, 1997.
</P>
<P>
By last year's deadline, Iranian security authorities were
able to collect only one-third of the total estimated one million
illegal unregistered weapons in the country.
</P>
<P>
After the deadline of last year, the authorities warned that
those who have refused to turn in their weapons were identified by
the police and would face imprisonment and death depending on
the circumstance under which their weapons would be confiscated.
</P>
<P>
As to the new deadline this year, Qadiriyan said, it is for
those who can "provide reasonable alibi for not turning their
weapons during the amnesty period which started from February
10, 1996."
</P>
<P>
He said that even those who had hunting rifles would have to
turn in their guns, adding that so far some 100,000 applications
had been submitted to the law enforcement centers for hunting
rifles.
</P>
<P>
The Iran-Iraq war from 1980 to 1988 brought about the
proliferation of arms in Iran. Arms are smuggled in and out of
Iran through Iran's border with Iraqi Kurdistan.
</P>
<P>
Light weapons produced by Iran's defense industries is said
to be smuggled out of the country because of corruption and
poor management in government bureaucracies.
</P>
<P>
Some sources here said that arms smuggling has always gone
hand in hand with narcotic trade. Iran's drug dealers are said
to have the state-of-the-art weaponry and have on occasion
overwhelmed Iranian anti-narcotic squads with their superior
firepower. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
