<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Steps up Effort to Tackle Child Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 16 (Xinhua) -- The British government steps up
its efforts to combat juvenile crime as the Home Secretary Michael
Howard will next week unveil proposals to place children aged
below 10 and their parents under curfews, local newspapers report
today.
</P>
<P>
Under Howard's proposals, to be published in a consultative
document next week, magistrates will be given new powers to impose
Parental Control Orders on parents of children aged under 10 in an
attempt to stop young delinquents sliding into a life of serious
crime.
</P>
<P>
Parents who refused to take responsibility for their children
could be ordered to remain at home under curfew, fined up to 1,000
pounds (1,620 US dollars), instructed to pay for the criminal
damage caused by their children or to do community work.
</P>
<P>
Under the plans, children likely to be subject to a Parental
Control Order will be identified by police, social workers,
teachers, health services and volunteers, who would investigate
the background of the child.
</P>
<P>
The Home Office believes that the proposals are necessary as
much criminal evidence suggest that children who offend in their
early years are most liable to become persistent offenders in
their teens.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that an estimated seven million crimes which
cost one billion pounds (1.62 billion US dollars) are committed
each year by youngsters under 18 in Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
