<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The World Bank and the Inter-Arab Investment
Guarantee Corporation (IAIGC) have signed a memorandum of
understanding to jointly boost investments on Arab projects.
</P>
<P>
Officials from both sides said it is a time when good economic
performance is registered in the region as a whole, a source from
the Kuwaiti-based IAIGC said today.
</P>
<P>
The source said the memo was signed here Saturday after
preliminary negotiations were conducted between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The document provides that the two agencies would cooperate in
promoting investments in Arab region, exchanging investment
information and holding seminars in the field.
</P>
<P>
The economy of the region has been picking up for the
past two years and most of the Arab countries are opening
windows to attract investments.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- With cement consumption per person exceeding 670
kilograms per year, Jordan has got one of the world's highest
rates in this regard, Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Local cement consumption amounted to 259 million tonnes last
year, compared with about 268 million tonnes in 1995, Abdul Elah
Al khatif, general manager of the Jordan cement factories
corporation (JCFC) was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The corporation's output increased by 3 percent in 1996 and
its exports shot up by 35 percent over the value recorded in 1995,
khatif said.
</P>
<P>
Cement production reached 3.51 million tonnes last year
compared with 3.42 million tonnes in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Khatif said the JCFC will develop six production line of cement
this year at the cost from 8 million dinars (about 11 million
U.S. dollars) to 10 million dinars (about 14 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's Minister of Industry and Trade Ali Abul
Ragheb has said that the kingdom is heading for intensive economic
activities with a wider opening of new markets for its products,
Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The intensive economic activities are facilitated by growing
Arab and foreign investments in Jordan's agriculture, industry and
tourism, the minister said here Saturday in response to a series
of foreign media reports on the kingdom's economy.
</P>
<P>
The minister dismissed as untrue earlier press reports that
some factories were shut down at the Sahab Industrial Estate. He
said the factories are actually opening additional branches in
other Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
He added that the estate is busily occupied and the government
is planning to establish additional industrial cities in all
governorates across the country to provide more opportunities to
investors.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian exports to the United States increased 10
percent in the period from January to October 1996 in comparison
to the same period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
A report prepared by the Trade Representation Office put the
volume of the Egyptian exports to the U.S. at 549.4 million U.S.
dollars during the period, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Ready-made clothes, textile, oil, agricultural produce,
foodstuffs and metallurgical products make up the bulk of Egyptian
exports to the U.S., which is Egypt's second largest trade partner.
</P>
<P>
The increasing Egyptian exports, however, are not confined to
the U.S. alone, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt managed to increase its exports of ready-made clothes to
Britain to 17.9 million pounds sterling (29 million dollars) in
the period from January to September 1996, a 42 percent rise
compared with the same period in 1995, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
