<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Central Banker Doubts 1999 Launch of Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Adding up to the widespread
scepticism over the single European currency, President of the
Bank of England Eddie George told a German magazine on Sunday that
he doubts the punctual start-up of the Euro by 1999.
</P>
<P>
Eddie told the German Capital economic magazine that he got the
impression that some countries had taken their participation in
the single currency Euro as a matter of prestige and few EU member
states can rush to meet the convergence criteria without second
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
"There is then the risk that the Euro would become a weak
currency rather than a strong one," he said.
</P>
<P>
George also noted that he did not see any big economic
disadvantage if Britain did not adopt the Euro from its start.
</P>
<P>
The EU is targeting to launch the Euro by January 1, 1999. But
scepticism is growing over whether the deadline can be met as few
members have been able to fulfill the criteria of the European
Monetary Union set by the Maastricht Treaty due to their sluggish
economy.
</P>
<P>
One of the criteria is that the budget deficit and national
debt of a member country must not exceed 3 and 60 percent
respectively of its gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
Germany, though upset by a post-war record jobless rate of 12.2
percent in January, seems to be the most optimistic among the EU
members.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest survey by the German public opinion
research institute Allensbach, which had questioned 600 leaders
from the German political and business circles, 71 percent of the
respondents believe that the single currency will be launched on
time. Only 27 percent said no.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
