<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Population to Remain Static Due to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 16 (Xinhua) -- A research survey said today
that Zimbabwe's population is poised to remain close to the
present 11 million in the next 30 years as an increased number of
its nationals succumb to the AIDS pandemic.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the Blair Research Institute and the
Welcome Center for Infectious Diseases of Oxford University in
the United Kingdom, noted a worrying trend that prevailing HIV
cases in rural areas are catching up with that in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
"Modest population decline is a real possibility. Under these
conditions, Zimbabwe's population in 30 years is likely to be
close to what it is now," said a statement issued here today by
the Zimbabwe Public Health Association, based on the survey.
</P>
<P>
It added that demographic projections also indicate a rapid
rise in mortality in rural areas with women dying at younger ages
than men. 
</P>
