<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Alarmed by the post-war record
joblessness of nearly 4.66 million for January, a senior German
trade union official today warned that the jobless figures could
exceed five million if government continued to cut spending.
</P>
<P>
Klaus Zwickel, head of the metalworkers' union IG Metall, told
the Bild am Sonntag newspaper that it would be a "lunacy" on the
part of the German government if it continued to cut spending and
reduce public sector demand.
</P>
<P>
Germany joblessness surged to 4,658,300 in January, or a rate
of 12.2 percent, the highest since 1933.
</P>
<P>
The German government had promised to cut unemployment by half
by the year 2000. Asked by the Bild newspaper on Wednesday if that
goal is still possible, Kohl said the government would hold on to
the goal. But he also admitted that it "is ambitious and would be
very difficult to reach".
</P>
<P>
Kohl stressed that job creation should take priority over all
other issues and called on both the trade unions and management to
make common efforts.
</P>
<P>
The German Federal Labour Office in Nuremberg, meanwhile, said
it did not expect another dramatic jump in unemployment. But a
spokesman of the Office on Saturday also said that "a lot depends
on the weather."  
</P>
