<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Deputy Prime Minister
Tansu Ciller is scheduled to leave tomorrow for Brussels to urge
NATO allies to help Turkey gain a full European Union (EU)
membership.
</P>
<P>
Ciller, also the foreign minister, is expected to meet with
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright Tuesday on the sideline
of the meeting of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in
Brussels, local tv stations reported tonight.
</P>
<P>
It is believed Ciller would emphasize at the meeting that NATO
enlargement should be linked to the expansion of the EU and its
designated defense arm, the Western European Union.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has threatened to veto NATO expansion unless the EU
admits it into the regional alliance.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said although it is all but impossible for
Ciller to get a clear-cut promise of securing Turkey's EU
admittance at the Brussels meeting, the issue will surely attract
anybody's attention.
</P>
<P>
Ciller said earlier this month that her government will make
every effort for a full EU membership in 1997 as Turkey is eager
to be part of the rapidly growing Europe.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission is considering the membership
applications by up to 10 possible candidates, but Turkey is kept
outside the body due to some controversial issues. Turkey made a
full membership application to the EU in April 1987. 
