<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Negotiators Pledge to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators concluded the first day of renewed peace talks
today, agreeing to pursue future peace without resorting to
violence.
</P>
<P>
The negotiating teams, headed by Foreign Minister David Levy
on the Israeli side and Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) on the
Palestinian side, held the talks in the Kibutz Maale Hamisha,
west of Jerusalem. This is the first peace talks since the two
sides signed the Hebron agreement last month.
</P>
<P>
Today's talks were described as good and positive, as both
sides pledged to refrain from violence in future peace process
and further the peace process with a sense of responsibility and
goodwill.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the talks, Levy termed the atmosphere of the
talks as "cordial", saying he was optimistic about the
continuation of future peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Levy also revealed that the two sides also agreed to initial
social activities aimed at bridging the gap between the two
peoples and build mutual trust.
</P>
<P>
This was in sharp contract to the tense atmosphere before the
talks.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the warning issued by Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat against Israel's
building of settlements, Levy said that if the Palestinian side
insisted on raising the settlement issue in the talks, they
would bear responsibility for ruining the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
As a result of today's talks, the two negotiating teams will
break into nine groups from Monday to deal with separate
issues.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of the peace talks on further implementing the
interim agreement was agreed at the summit meeting between
Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu last
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Under the Hebron pact, the two sides will hold talks on
settling issues stipulated in the interim accord, including the
opening of safe passages between West Bank and Gaza Strip, a
Gaza airport and Gaza sea port, and development of economic and
security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The talks are expected to continue for months or even longer
because of the difficulties of the issues and differences
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Moshe Fogel, Director of Israel's Government Press Office, who
serves as the spokesman for the talks, said that the two sides
would face "increasing difficulties" in future talks.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think that anything can be concluded easily. But I
think they can be concluded because what we want to do is we
want to honor the agreements signed by the previous government,"
he told the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman stressed that both sides should be
committed to refraining from resorting to violence in the
future, and resolving disputes only through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that both sides will understand that negotiations at
the peace table is the only option for working out the
disputes," Fogel added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
