<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Takes Measures to Save Carpet Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government today
took a major step to save the traditional carpet industry by
allowing dealers to retain the hard currency they earn and
travelers to take 12 square meters of rug out of Iran.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Tehran Radio reported that the decision was
made at a meeting presided over by Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
Beginning from the new Iranian month of Esfand starting
Wednesday, the rug exporters can keep 100 percent of the hard
currency they earn and use them to import permissible items, it
said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that those who plan to travel abroad can take
12 square meters of rug with them now instead of three square
meters rug in the past.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Iranian Parliament endorsed a bill to allow
carpet export dealers to retain 100 percent of the hard currency
they earn in a bid to save the carpet industry.
</P>
<P>
Formerly, carpet export dealers had to turn in the hard currency
they earn from the export and receive equivalent rials in export
rate -- 3,000 rials for one U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
But, one dollar is against 4,600 rials in the black market
now.
</P>
<P>
Iran's carpet industry had suffered a lot from the policy set
by the central bank as exporters had no interest in the business
since they could not make profit.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the export volume of carpet dropped half from one
billion dollars to about 500 million dollars last year. Many
Iranian carpets could not find market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
