<HEADLINE> China Tourism Set Record in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 17 (Xinhua) -- More than 51.12 million
overseas tourists visited China in 1996, setting a new record and
enjoying a year-on-year increase of 10.22 percent.
</P>
<P>
The country's international tourism earnings reached 10.2
billion US dollars in 1996, which also reached a new peak and
increased by 16.81 percent, China National Tourism Administration
has announced.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the majority of the tourists visiting the
Chinese mainland last year were from Hong Kong and Macao, with
their numbers coming to 42.49 million, up 9.38 percent over the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Tourists from foreign countries numbered 6.74 million, a growth
of 14.57 percent.
</P>
<P>
There were 1.73 million Taiwan tourists, up 13.16 percent, and
overseas Chinese topped 154,600, a jump of 33.49 percent.
</P>
<P>
Of the tourism income, 9.18 billion US dollars were spent by
those making overnight stays, with the rest coming from
day-trippers.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that all of China's 15 source countries
and regions for tourism recorded growth in the number of tourists
sent to China, with visitors from Japan, the largest source,
witnessing a rise of 18.7 percent; guests of the Republic of
Korea, the second largest at 31.1 percent; and the United States
ranking third with 12 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
