<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Parliament Urges Government to Borrow Less </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian parliament, worried
about the country's foreign debt of more than 8 billion U.S.
dollars, has called on the government to borrow less foreign money.
</P>
<P>
Saying in a resolution that the government has borrowed too
much, parliament deputies urged the Cabinet of Ministers to submit
a draft legislation to limit borrowing.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's foreign debt is currently some 10 percent of the
country's gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Vadim Hetman, former chairman of Ukraine's central bank, called
on his fellow deputies to set a ceiling on the foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
"Parliament must get tougher on the government so that it does
not get carried away with foreign aid that must be repaid," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Agrarian faction member Serhy Dovhan criticized the practice of
using foreign loans to buy imported machinery instead of
subsidizing domestic manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Ukraine borrowed 187 million dollars from the
U.S. Export-Import Bank to buy 1,049 harvesters from John Deere
Tractors, a U.S. company.
</P>
<P>
Dovhan said the deal has made tens of thousands of workers at
local harvester-making plants jobless. And the country's huge
collective farms have great difficulties in adapting the
U.S. harvesters to local conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
