<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Reports on "Religious Suppression" in China Refuted (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Normal religious activities of religious organizations,
religious sites and their legitimate rights and interests are
protected by the law in China, and no one should violate these
rights, it said.
</P>
<P>
It went on to note that the Chinese criminal code stipulates in
article 147 that government functionaries who illegally deprive
citizens of their reasonable freedom of religious belief or
violate customs of ethnic groups, shall face imprisonment less
than two years or criminal detention, if the case is serious.
</P>
<P>
But the columnist, having no knowledge of these facts, has
accused China of "harsh crackdowns" and "has been intentionally
attempting to confuse black and white," the article said.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times' "concern" over China's Catholics inevitably
reminds people of the history of that religion, which dates back
more than 400 years in the country, the article said.
</P>
<P>
Before the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949,
the Chinese Catholics as well as Chinese clergymen were under the
control of churches of dozens of western countries, and had no say
in their own affairs, the article said, adding that, for example,
in the 143 parishes in China at that time, only 20 bishops were
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
After New China was founded, the Chinese Catholics started
to operate their churches independently. According to the Chinese
Catholic Church, over 60,000 people were baptized annually since
then, and the number of Catholic followers has now reached four
million.
</P>
<P>
Over 4,000 churches and public sites of worship have been
re-opened. In addition, more than 20 theological seminaries have
been set up, in which over 1,200 students are receiving higher
religious education.
</P>
<P>
Since 1988, over 600 young people have become godparents, and
more than one million Bibles and other books have been printed,
the article revealed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Reports on "Religious Suppression" in China Refuted (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Washington Times columnist, however, seemed to take a
special interest in the group of Chinese Protestants, the
article noted.
</P>
<P>
As known to all, it said, China in 1949 had only 700,000-plus
Protestants, but the Washington Times columnist alleged that the
figure has surged to at least 75 million.
</P>
<P>
"Aside from the questionable credibility of this number, it is
still far from convincing for the US columnist to use the figure
as evidence for the existence of religious persecution in China,"
the article argued.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the will of the public, the Chinese
government has always protected the rights of both the Chinese
citizens and foreigners in China to practice normal religious
activities through proper application of laws and regulations, the
article noted.
</P>
<P>
In January of 1994, the Chinese government issued "Regulations
on the Management of Foreigners' Religious Activities in China"
and "Regulations on the Management of the Places of Religious
Activities."
</P>
<P>
"It was the first time since its founding in 1949 that the
People's Republic of China had ever issued special laws on
religions, which was a significant step in the country's legal
development concerning religious affairs," the article commented.
</P>
<P>
It went on to say that both regulations have been designed to
give full protection to the freedom of religious beliefs, and to
firmly safeguard social and public benefits at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Any religious activities, either by the Chinese citizens or by
foreigners in China, must follow Chinese laws and regulations, and
do no harm to the social and public good in China, it added.
</P>
<P>
While these regulations are just fundamental laws that will be
adopted in any country with a legal system, it continued,
columnists of the New York Times and the Washington Times have
insisted on labeling them as "religious suppression."
</P>
<P>
"This gives us every reason to believe that they are trying to
challenge the social and public benefits not only in China, but in
all countries with a legal system as well," the article said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Reports on "Religious Suppression" in China Refuted (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It said these US columnists hoped that the Chinese government
would adopt a laissez-faire attitude toward illegal activities
under the guise of religion, which not only would infringe on the
social and public benefits, but also surely harm the normal
religious activities.
</P>
<P>
"What on earth are the motives of these columnists of the New
York Times and the Washington Times? " the article asked, saying
it is quite possible that they are trying to suppress other
countries' religious freedom in the name of anti-religious
suppression.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times columnist expounded at length on the
so-called unofficial organizations forced to turn underground. In
fact, there is only one Catholic Church in China, which includes
both the Chinese Catholic Bishops College and the China Patriotic
Catholic Association. They share the same beliefs with Catholic
Churches in other parts of the world, and are part of world
Catholicism, the article explained.
</P>
<P>
It also said there is no need to be reticent of the fact that
in inland China, there really exist a few people who, with the
support and under the command of some overseas forces, refuse to
obey the government's laws and regulations, and persist in various
illegal activities in disguise of Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
No government in the world will ever tolerate or be blind to
illegal behavior, the article pointed out, and freedom bestowed to
any evil cult is the gravest violation of civil rights.
</P>
<P>
"It is unthinkable even for a country like the U.S., which
always flaunts the banner of `absolute freedom', to grant such
freedom to evil cults like the Aum Shinri Kyo, which take pleasure
in killing," it added.
</P>
<P>
It went on to persuade the New York Times and the Washington
Times, which it described as "mass media members with some
influence in the U.S.", to stop misleading the public by
publishing articles based on specious rumors.
</P>
<P>
"We also suggest columnists of the two newspapers write
something that can withstand close scrutiny with verifiable facts,
and that they be responsible to the readers, instead of talking
nonsense, pushing the US government to challenge the social
and public good in a country on the other side of the ocean even
on the expense of the public interests of the U.S. itself," the
article concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
