<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hiroshima Asks U.S. to Suspend Subcritical Nuke Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Hiroshima Mayor Takashi Hiraoka
of Japan asked today the U.S. government to suspend a subcritical
or nonexplosive nuclear test scheduled for this spring.
</P>
<P>
The request, said a Kyodo News report, was contained in a
letter addressed to U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Hiraoka cited an opinion handed down last July by the
International Court of Justice that the threat or use of nuclear
weapons is generally contrary to the rules of international law.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese mayor also reportedly mentioned, in his letter,
the United Nations General Assembly's adoption last September of
the comprehensive nuclear test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. test "will heighten international mistrust,
increase the danger of nuclear proliferation, and dampen the
efforts of the international community to abolish nuclear weapons."
</P>
<P>
On August 6, 1945, a U.S. atomic bomb was dropped on Hiroshima,
destroying 90 percent of the city and ultimately killing at least
200,000 people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets German Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen today expressed his hope that
Sino-German business cooperation can be further expanded.
</P>
<P>
Qian made the remark here this afternoon when meeting with
Manfred Stolpe, minister-president of Brandenburg of Germany, and
his party.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Qian said that China and Germany have good
cooperative relations, especially the vital and close cooperation
in the economic field.
</P>
<P>
The exchanges between different localities of the two countries
are necessary for strengthening bilateral cooperation, added Qian.
</P>
<P>
Noting that there are some German business people accompanying
Stolpe on his China trip, Qian said he hopes that business people
from the two countries can make use of their contacts to find
opportunities for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said that China and Germany enjoy a great potential for
cooperation in the power and telecommunications sectors, and that
he wants the two sides to expand cooperation between small- and
medium-sized enterprises while improving ties between large
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Stolpe said that Brandenburg has traditional close relations
with China, and this visit is aimed at further sealing the bond.
</P>
<P>
This visit is also aimed at learning more about China, and
seeking opportunities and possibilities for expanding ties with
China, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said he is convinced that the businessmen in his entourage
will have successful exchanges with their Chinese counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The German visitors are here as guests of the Chinese People's
Institute of Foreign Affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
