<HEADLINE> Li Peng Solicits Suggestions from Non-Communists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng today
solicited opinions from non-Communist Party senior officials about
the draft Report on Government Work, which he will deliver at the
upcoming annual session of China's top legislature.
</P>
<P>
Participants at the forum this afternoon agreed that 1996
marked a good start in the implementation of the country's Ninth
Five-year Plan (1996-2000), with sustainable economic growth, slower
rate of inflation and good cultural and ethical progress.
</P>
<P>
They said that the draft report objectively sums up China's
achievements and problems over the past year, and points out the
work priorities for this year.
</P>
<P>
Prior to this forum, the officials held discussions on the
draft report.
</P>
<P>
At today's forum, many of them offered suggestions for the
reform of state-owned enterprises, more investment in education,
arable land protection, stricter macro-control over capital
construction, reunification of the motherland, family planning,
anti-corruption and crackdown on crimes.
</P>
<P>
The premier thanked the participants for their good
suggestions, saying that the ideas will be included in the report
after some study. 
</P>
</TEXT>
