<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright began a world tour in
Rome, trying to consolidate NATO's position on eastward expansion
and its relations with Russia before arriving in Moscow on
Thursday. Later, she flew to Bonn and was scheduled to arrive
Monday in Paris, where she will attempt to smooth over ties that
became strained after a series of disagreements last year.
</P>
<P>
-- A Peruvian newspaper published details of a secret
Government plan to rescue the 72 hostages still held at the
Japanese Embassy residence in Lima. Officials confirmed the plan,
but noted that such preparation was routine and that they were
hopeful that the crises could still be resolved without force.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The American Jewish community faces a serious rift of
historic proportions, which caused by the "Who is a Jew" debate in
Israel, promoted by the upcoming vote in the Israeli parliament on
a bill that would deny legitimacy to all but Orthodox conversions.
</P>
<P>
-- The older brother of former Mexican president Carlos
Salinas helped arrange a 4 million U.S. dollar payment intended
for the release of a drug trafficker detained on cocaine charges
in 1993, according to U.S. documents. 
</P>
