<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest City Pays Attention To Sewage Disposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 17 (Xinhua) -- International bidding began
today on the second phase of a waste water disposal project now
underway here in China's largest city.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is expected to dispose of 1.7 million cubic
meters of urban sewage after completion, will mainly benefit the
city's southern area.
</P>
<P>
A 51.8-km sewer pipe will be laid underground from the
southwest area of Shanghai to the mouth of the Yangtze River. The
pipe will extend through three districts in the the city's
southern part and the Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
The project, with a total investment of five billion yuan (602
million US dollars), is to begin in March. Its main part is
expected to be finished by the end of 1999, said an official with
the municipal government.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has issued 250 million dollars in loans for the
project, figures show.
</P>
<P>
The city has finished the first phase of the work, which can
dispose of 1.2 million cubic meters of urban sewage, and has
benefited the city's northern region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
