<HEADLINE> Nepal to Pursue Foreign Policy for Economic Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Nepal will redefine its
foreign policy priorities in order to promote the country's
economic interests in the world, Prime Minister Sher Bahadur Deuba
said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a program held by Nepal Council of World Affairs
here today, Deuba said that Nepal will have to build new bridges
and lay out new avenues to the outside world on the foundations of
shared economic interests.
</P>
<P>
The government has adopted a policy to enhance economic
diplomacy aimed at expanding the country's exports, attracting
direct foreign investment and promoting tourism through
strengthening bilateral and regional cooperation, he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Nepal is a country locked between India and China,
the prime minister said the country must strive to turn its
geographical disadvantage into economic advantage of readily
available markets for its products and services.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need of further cooperation in the
seven-nation South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation
(SAARC) to tackle regional problems and to maximize common
benefits of South Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The SAARC groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives,
Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Nepal has established an International Business Forum to foster
a closer and mutually complementary interaction between the
government and the private sector to achieve the country's
economic objectives, Deuba said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, an Economic Relations and Coordination
Division has also been set up under the Foreign Ministry to pursue
effective economic diplomacy and Nepali missions abroad have been
directed to take up the challenge of economic thrust while dealing
with the country's external relations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
