<HEADLINE> Top French, U.S. Diplomats to Attend NATO Informal Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 17 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Herve de
Charette and his U.S. counterpart, Madeleine Albright, will attend
an informal meeting of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) in Brussels on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said the
two top diplomats will attend a "special meeting" of the Atlantic
Council at the Belgian capital after de Charette meets the
visiting U.S. secretary of state later today in Paris.
</P>
<P>
"This extraordinary and informal meeting will allow one to make
the point of the on-going debate within the NATO on the reform and
enlargement of the alliance, as well as its relations with Russia
and Ukraine," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said French officials will go to Brussels "with a strong
hope that a good agreement with Russia be reached before the
(NATO) Madrid summit scheduled for July."
</P>
<P>
During a brief visit to Russia on February 2, French President
Jacques Chirac said an agreement between NATO and Russia was
likely to be reached before the Madrid summit.
</P>
<P>
How to negotiate such an agreement with Russia has become a new
dispute between the United States and France, after Washington
rejected a French proposal to hold a summit by the United States,
Russia, France, Britain and Germany to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said
Moscow must be treated on an equal stand with NATO members when it
is invited to negotiate a charter on NATO-Russia relations.
</P>
<P>
He also said any military agreement between NATO and Russia
should have a "stringent character" to "appease the fears" of
Russia over NATO's eastward expansion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
