<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Foreign Markets Sent More Tourists to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Japan, the Republic of Korea
(ROK), the United States, and Russia continued to be the four
largest source countries of China's international tourism industry
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, which was the seventh largest source in 1995, placed
fifth in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Japan, which has been China's largest tourism source for years,
sent 1.5488 million tourists to China last year, a rise of 18.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
ROK, which surpassed the US to become China's second largest
market in 1995, retained its ranking in 1996 by sending 693,900
tourists to China, which represented an impressive increase of
31.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists from the US stood at 576,400, a rise of
12 percent. There were 555,900 Russian tourists, up 13.6 percent.
Arrivals from Malaysia were counted at 298,500, an increase of
18.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The latest statistics of the China National Tourism
Administration indicate that 6.7443 million overseas tourists
travelled to China in 1996.
</P>
<P>
While the number of tourists from all of the fifteen source
countries increased, those from Japan, ROK, US, Russia, Malaysia,
the Philippines, Britain, Thailand, and Canada witnessed
double-digit growth.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also showed that over 50 million overseas tourists
visited China's inland areas in 1996: of this group, 42.495
million were from Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
China's tourism foreign exchange earnings topped 10.2 billion
US dollars last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
