<HEADLINE> India Renews Offer to Resume Indo-Pak Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister Deve
Gowda today renewed his offer of an early resumption of Indo-Pak
dialogue at appropriate level.
</P>
<P>
In a greeting message to Nawaz Sharif on his assumption of
office of prime minister of Pakistan, Gowda said, "We are willing
to have wide-ranging comprehensive talks on all issues of mutual
concern."
</P>
<P>
"I have noted the positive statements made by your excellency
to improve relations between our two countries. I reciprocate your
sentiments in full measure. We believe there are a number of
opportunities for mutually beneficial cooperation. We approach
these opportunities in a positive and constructive spirit, for it
is our firm conviction that cooperation between us will lead to
genuine benefit for both our peoples," Gowda said in the message.
</P>
<P>
There has been no official dialogue between the two countries
since January 1994 when the foreign secretary level talks ended
abruptly.
</P>
<P>
Last year Gowda offered a wide-ranging dialogue with Pakistan.
During his election campaign early this year and after his
impressive victory, Nawaz Sharif made positive statements seeking
"serious dialogue" with India. "This is a very good time to have
serious talks with India. We should live like good neighbors
instead of blaming each other for our problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Indian prime minister welcomed the positive signals from
Sharif and offered full cooperation for resumption of the dialogue
between the two countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
