<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhou Nan Toasts Hong Kong's Smooth Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 17 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Chinese
official said here today that nothing could affect the general
situation of Hong Kong, which will surely realize smooth
transition in an auspicious and prosperous atmosphere in 100-odd
days.
</P>
<P>
Hosting a spring reception this evening attended by 3,000-odd
people, Zhou Nan, director of the Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong
Branch, said: "After going through ebb and flow over the past 12
years of transition, Hong Kong is heading for a final point of
glory."
</P>
<P>
"In four months' time, Hong Kong will put an end to the
centurial colonial rule, return to the motherland and enter a new
era of history," Zhou said. "For all Chinese around the world, the
long-awaited moment will come soon."
</P>
<P>
The domestic and international situation is becoming more and
more favorable to the smooth transition of Hong Kong, said the
Chinese official who also pointed to the surging love of China and
of Hong Kong and the increasing confidence of local and
international investors.
</P>
<P>
Zhou noted: "Man-made obstacles are being eliminated one by
one, and some pessimistic views about Hong Kong's future are
evaporating. Now we are fully confident to say that no matter what
disturbances may occur before handover, they can not affect the
overall situation."
</P>
<P>
He attributed the encouraging situation in Hong Kong to the
full implementation of Deng Xiaoping's great concept of "one
country, two systems", to the central government's policies and
principles concerning Hong Kong and to the rapid progress made in
China's reform and economic construction.
</P>
<P>
Finally, he praised the efforts made by Hong Kong compatriots
in maintaining Hong Kong's prosperity and stability and in
preparing the establishment of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
In conclusion, he called on Hong Kong people in all sectors to
render great support to the first Chief Executive and the
Provisional Legislative Council of the HKSAR, so as to ensure Hong
Kong's sustained prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, the first Chief Executive of the HKSAR, attend
the gathering and delivered a short speech. As many recent opinion
surveys show, the majority of the Hong Kong people have full
confidence in Hong Kong's return to China, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tung spoke highly of the great political wisdom embodied in the
principles of "one country, two systems" and "Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong". He call on Hong Kong people to take a more
optimistic and positive attitude in greeting Hong Kong's return to
the motherland in the last few months before handover.  
</P>
</TEXT>
