<HEADLINE> US Reports on "Religious Suppression" in China Refuted (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Xinhua News Agency published
an article today, refuting criticism made by some US media against
China's religious policy and its so-called large-scale
"suppression of religious activities."
</P>
<P>
The New York Times and the Washington Times published a series
of reports recently attacking China's policy of freedom of
religion by alleging that the government has launched a massive
campaign to suppress religious activities.
</P>
<P>
They also complained that the US government's attitude toward
China was "not firm enough" on the question of human rights policy
because of its "commercial interests," according to the article
entitled "Some US Columnists are Challenging the Public Interests."
</P>
<P>
Their accusations against China's "harsh crackdowns" upon
religion were based solely on billboards carrying messages that
oppose illegal religious activities, which had been posted "in a
certain town of a certain county of a certain province," the
article said.
</P>
<P>
And the newspapers determined with full certainty that China
has initiated a "new wave of religious suppression" across the
country, in order to shore up its current drive to promote ethical
and cultural progress.
</P>
<P>
These allegations are groundless, the article maintained.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times stated that "last spring, thousands of
paramilitary police supported by armored car units and
helicopters" destroyed a Catholic church in Hebei Province. This
sensational description made people believe a war broke out there,
the article said.
</P>
<P>
Perhaps the New York Times columnist imagined the church was a
fortress, and that armored cars and helicopters were needed to
destroy it, the article said, commenting that "Isn't this rumor a
bit too strange and fantastic?"
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
