<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seasonal Factors Lead to Higher Inflation Rate in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Inflation continued to rise in
Germany last month, with consumer prices going up by 1.8 percent
over a year earlier, compared with the 1.4 percent increase in
December, the Federal Statistics Office reported today.
</P>
<P>
In month-on-month terms, the cost of living index for private
households rose by 0.5 percent from December in western Germany
and by 0.7 percent in the eastern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
Experts stressed that the increase was mainly due to seasonal
and weather-influenced factors and would not shake Germany's
relatively high price stability.
</P>
<P>
They noted that the prices of seasonal food grew by 7 to 14
percent and those of heating oil by 28 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
