<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Reports on "Religious Suppression" in China Refuted (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The article included another example of a Washington Times
report on China's destruction of illegally-built graves in East
China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Some newly affluent farmers in Zhejiang Province built the
graves randomly without plan, destroying all the green trees on
hill slopes. The local people were very angry about this. With
the guide and help of the local authorities, the graves were
removed and rearranged in areas designated by the government, the
article said.
</P>
<P>
But the Washington Times described the situation by saying "in
Zhejiang Province alone, 15,000 religious sites were destroyed in
the first six months of 1996."
</P>
<P>
The article wonders whether graves in the United States are
considered "religious sites."
</P>
<P>
The New York Times columnist was engaged in deliberate
misrepresentation by "calling a stag a horse," the article
comments.
</P>
<P>
The columnist alleged that "the harsh treatment of Catholics in
China dates to the 1950's," and the authorities "see religion as a
vehicle for political organization, dissent or outright opposition
to the Party's role."
</P>
<P>
However, facts tell another story, the article pointed out,
saying that the People's Republic of China declared at the time of
its foundation that New China protects religious freedom, which is
guaranteed ever since its first Constitution.
</P>
<P>
China is a country with many varieties of religions, and has
around 100 million religious followers. Respect for and protection
of religious freedom have been China's fundamental policy toward
religious issues, and are safeguarded by the law, the article said.
</P>
<P>
In the Constitution, the general rules of the civil law, and
laws on autonomous regions, military service, compulsory
education, election of deputies to people's congresses, and
organization of village committees, the provision has been
included to protect religious freedom, the article adds.
</P>
</TEXT>
