<HEADLINE> Rightist Rams Car in Kochi Governor's Residence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 17 (Xinhua) -- A 27-year-old rightist was
arrested today after ramming a van into the official residence of
Kochi Governor Daijiro Hashimoto in Kochi, western Japan, news
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The car driven by Yuji Morimoto, a member of the local rightist
group Taikosha, destroyed a portion of the front gate, the reports
quoted police as saying. No one was hurt in the incident.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto, the younger brother of Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto, told reporters he was asleep and did not hear anything
when the incident occurred, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Police sources said that the attack might be connected with the
50-year-old governor's speech on February 1 in which he questioned
the rational of having "kimigayo," a song about the emperor, as
Japan's national anthem, according to the reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
