<HEADLINE> Albright, Kinkel Agree on NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and her German counterpart, Klaus Kinkel, said
today they hold identical views on NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference after their meeting here Monday
morning, Albright and Kinkel also said they had agreed on the
inclusion of Russia in a new security system.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they both expressed reservations about a French
proposal for a meeting by France, Germany, Britain, the United
States and Russia to discuss Russia's role in NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
France proposed that leaders of the five nations meet before a
scheduled summit of the 16 NATO members in July in Madrid, Spain,
on restructuring the Western military alliance.
</P>
<P>
The July meeting also aims to consider NATO's post-Cold War
relations with Russia, which has been against NATO expansion, and
the alliance's first recruitment of new members.
</P>
<P>
Albright said Washington counts the "substance," rather than
the procedure of reaching an agreement with Russia on the planned
NATO eastward expansion into the former East bloc.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel stressed that for the moment, Western countries must try
all possibilities to secure Russia's content on NATO enlargement.
</P>
</TEXT>
