<HEADLINE> Jordan: Efforts Continue to Free Prisoners from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN February 17 (Xinhua) - At least two Gulf Arab countries
are continuing efforts with the Kuwaiti government to secure the
release of the dozens of Jordanians jailed in the emirate, but no
definite outcome of the efforts has emerged yet, Jordan Times
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper, citing diplomatic source here Sunday, said Oman and
Qatar are currently make the efforts in response to a specific
Jordanian request following a recent report that Kuwaiti security
forces had stormed a prison and beat up Jordanian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The Omani and Qatari ambassadors visited the prison and then
told the Jordanian government that the prisoners were treated
well, and the reported violence was in connection with the
toughening of the prison administration following incidents of
drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanians are held separately from those serving sentences on
drug smuggling charges.
</P>
<P>
Since the visit, an intense effort has been launched to
convince the Kuwaiti government to release all the Jordanian
prisoners held on political charges of collaborating with the Iraqis
during the occupation of Kuwait, which ended by the Gulf War in
1991..
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, other countries friendly to
Jordan also joined the efforts to free the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan, the Regent, said Saturday after
a meeting of the Council of Ministers that Arab mediation was
continuing.
</P>
<P>
Around 60 Jordanians are serving sentences in Kuwait after the
state security court found them guilty of "collaborating with
Iraqis." 
</P>
</TEXT>
