<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Eliminate Leprosy in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Health
Department is targeting to eliminate leprosy as a public health
problem by the end of 1998 as the number of leprosy cases
continues to decrease in the country.
</P>
<P>
Since the country launched a campaign against the skin disease
in 1994, the country's leprosy incidence decreased to 1.4 per
10,000 people by the end of 1996 from 1.7 in 1995 and 2.5 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, about 2,668 new leprosy cases were detected in the
country with a population of nearly 70 million, a sharp decrease
from the 1991 level of 7,169 cases.
</P>
<P>
With this development, Health Secretary Carmencita Reodica said
attaining the elimination of leprosy in the country by the end of
1998 is no longer impossible.
</P>
<P>
The Health Department's leprosy elimination effort is further
boosted by the availability of an effective drug combination known
as multi-drug therapy introduced by the World Health Organization
in 1981. After a week receiving the therapy, leprosy patients
become non-infectious.
</P>
<P>
Currently, leprosy is endemic in about 35 of the 73 provinces
and municipalities in the country, with Sulu province in the
southern Philippines having the highest incidence of 16.2 per
10,000 people.
</P>
<P>
With leprosy treatment no longer requiring confinement at the
leprosarium or sanitarium, the Health Department is considering
converting the current eight leprosaria into general hospitals.
</P>
</TEXT>
