<HEADLINE> Primakov: Moscow Has Right to Defend Interests in NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov has reiterated Moscow's right to defend its
interests in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization's (NATO)
eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
In a TV interview aired Monday night, Primakov made the
standing Russian position clear again while noting that his
country doesn't have a veto power against the NATO enlargement.
</P>
<P>
The remarks, made to Russia's Independent Television, was
broadcast in the same program as those of U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, who will be here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said NATO should sign an agreement to eliminate
Russia's concerns about its expansion by prohibiting the
alliance's military facilities to come near Russia's boders.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, the senior Russian official said, should also
include provisions calling for NATO's transformation from a
military organization into a political one.
</P>
<P>
In her TV interview, Albright stressed that NATO's expansion is
not directed towards Russia, but is aimed at creating a new
mechanism for the security of Central and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Pointing out that Russia will have a say, not a veto, in NATO's
expansion, Albright said Russia should sign a charter to establish
a consultative mechanism with the Western military alliance.
</P>
<P>
The top U.S. diplomat expressed her hope that Russia and her
country would maintain mutual confidence and continue to step up
cooperation after the NATO enlargement.
</P>
<P>
The new U.S. state secretary is scheduled to arrive here on
Thursday on her first official foreign tour and hold talks with
Primakov on NATO's planned eastward expansion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
