<HEADLINE> People Have High Hopes of Elected Govt: Army Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 17 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Pakistani
Army official said here today that the army hopes the new
government will take effective measures for political and economic
stability.
</P>
<P>
Chief of Pakistan's Army Staff Gen. Jehangir Karamat said that
while the masses had high hopes of the elected representatives,
"we are also equally hopeful that stability will come and national
matters will be deliberated upon and solved."
</P>
<P>
Karamat made the remarks to the media after Nawaz Sharif's
oath-taking ceremony as Pakistan's new prime minister held at the
Presidential House.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the Kashmir issue, Karamat said that during the
previous era, "there were high expectations of a peaceful
settlement of the Kashmir issue. Now, again, there are high
expectations."
</P>
<P>
Kashmir, he said, was a basic problem "and cannot be thrown on
the back burner."
</P>
<P>
Answering a question, Karamat said that inflation was required
to be controlled first, as the element of inflation lessened the
size of the budget.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the newly-formed Council for Defense and National
Security (CDNS), the Army chief said it was up to the government
and the parliament to decide about it.
</P>
<P>
"It's a useful forum for discussion and not for decisions", he
said.  
</P>
