<HEADLINE> British Fire Experts to Fight Ship Fire in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 17 (Xinhua) -- British chemical fire experts
have flown in to fight the fire aboard the Hongkong-registered
cargo ship MV Oyster Bay in Mombasa port, the East African
Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
The vessel loaded with hydrogen peroxide, among other
chemicals, was still ablaze on Sunday although Kenya Ports
Authority tried hard to control the fire.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to extinguish the fire with sea water have proved
futile as the burning chemicals are reactivated by it, according
to port sources.
</P>
<P>
The British experts were brought in on Sunday by the vessel's
insurers as experts on the scene refrained from opening hatch
number four where the fire started, saying that they could only
do so when the Lloyds team arrived.
</P>
<P>
Some of the cargo was destined for Dar es Salaam but was being
offloaded to pave the way for experts to reach hatch number four.
</P>
<P>
Marine engineers and surveyors said that if the British
experts failed to establish the cause of the fire, they would
take the vessel to dry dock. 
</P>
</TEXT>
