<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Vice President Visits Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Bong-Suh Lee, vice president
of the Asian Development Bank (ADB), concluded his visit to Sri
Lanka today.
</P>
<P>
During his 3-day stay here, he called on President Chandrika
Kumaratunga and had discussions with Minister of Foreign Affairs
Lakshman Kadiragamar and other ministers on matters of mutual
interest relating to the ADB's overall operational program in Sri
Lanka, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka began borrowing from the ADB in 1969, and by the end
of 1996 had received 78 loans totaling 1.8 billion U.S. dollars.
In 1996, the bank approved two loans for Sri Lanka amounting to 44
million dollars for emergency rehabilitation, petroleum facilities
project and a North Central province rural development project.
</P>
<P>
Loan disbursements were 149 million dollars in 1996, which was
much higher than in recent years, according to the sources .
</P>
<P>
The bank's operational strategy in Sri Lanka aims to reduce
poverty and unemployment through higher economic growth. Five new
bank loans totaling 155 million dollars, and ten technical
assistance grants amounting to 6 million dollars, in the
agriculture, social infrastructure, transport and environment
sectors in Sri Lanka are scheduled in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
