<HEADLINE> Profile: Nawaz Sharif, Pakistan's New Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Nawaz Sharif, who sat on the
opposition bench for three years, today came back to the office of
Pakistan's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The 46-year-old Sharif, leader of the Pakistan Muslim League
(N), was sworn in today as the country's 8th prime minister since
1988, at an oath-taking ceremony administered by President Farooq
Leghari.
</P>
<P>
A law graduate from Pakistan's oldest seat of learning, the
Punjab University, Sharif is a wealthy industrialist. His family
owns Ittefaq Industrial conglomerate, one of Pakistan's largest
with interest in metal, sugar and textiles.
</P>
<P>
Sharif was inducted into politics in 1981 at the age of 30 when
he was appointed finance minister of Pakistan's most populous
province of Punjab.
</P>
<P>
Three years later, he became the youngest chief minister of
Punjab province where he developed a well-deserved reputation for
being an able, hands-on administrator.
</P>
<P>
He was re-elected to this position in 1988.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990 elections which followed the dismissal of Benazir's
first government by the then president, Ghulam Ishaq Khan, Sharif
led a group of nine parties under the banner of the Islamic
Democratic Alliance to victory.
</P>
<P>
With a two-thirds majority in the National Assembly, Sharif
launched a bold economic program involving lavish spending on
infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
Sharif's stint as prime minister, which lasted only 30 months,
was marked by an accent on opening up the economy, energizing the
entrepreneurial skills of the people and working as a bridge
builder among the provinces of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
It was during this period that Sharif showed that he was a doer
who delivers.
</P>
<P>
When his elected government was dismissed arbitrarily by Ghulam
Ishaq Khan on April 18, 1993, Sharif's defiance earned him popular
support across the length and breadth of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
As prime minister of a coalition government, which included
Pakistan's largest religious party, he pursued economic policies
with a free-market orientation and gave a nod toward extending the
influence of Islam.
</P>
<P>
However, the Jammat-e-Islami left the coalition after Sharif
supported the United States in the Persian Gulf War and backed a
UN plan to install an interim government in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Since the dismissal of the Benazir government last November,
the PML chief has emerged as the likeliest alternative to his
political rival, whose popularity fell amid economic troubles and
persistent allegation of corruption by her husband, Asif Ali
Zardari.
</P>
<P>
In the February 3 general elections, Sharif's PML(N) won a
landslide victory by collecting 135 seats in the 217-member
National Assembly while the Pakistan People's Party led by Benazir
managed only 17 seats.
</P>
<P>
Sharif promised that if he comes to power, the first priority
will be to revamp Pakistan's staggering economy.
</P>
<P>
He also vowed to carry on the accountability process, abolish
rampant corruption and improve law and order situation in the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
