<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea to Open Financial Market in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 17 (Xinhua) -- South Korea plans to complete
the opening of the financial market in 1998, two years after
Koreans are allowed to establish various financial service
companies, the Ministry of Finance and Economy said here today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that from this year it will completely
abolish the market need test requirements for the establishment of
foreign bank branches, securities companies, insurance firms and
investment trust companies.
</P>
<P>
Prior establishment of representative offices will no longer be
required to set up investment trust company branches from December
1, 1998. The requirement for investment advisory companies was
abolished last month.
</P>
<P>
The ceiling on aggregate foreign ownership in existing
securities companies will be scrapped by December 1, 1998, while
foreign banks and securities houses will be allowed to establish
subsidiaries in South Korea from December 1998.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, foreign investment advisory firms will be permitted
to open subsidiaries from December 1, 1997 and investment trust
companies from December 1, 1998, according to the ministry.
</P>
</TEXT>
