<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pupils, Soldiers Most Exposed To HIV In Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 17 (Xinhua) -- School pupils and
members of the armed forces appear to be particularly exposed to
infection by the Human Immuno Virus (HIV).
</P>
<P>
The finding was presented in a paper submitted to a doctors
conference held here recently.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that school going pupils and people in camps or
doing similar group activity were among the most exposed groups
to HIV infection.
</P>
<P>
The city of Dar es Salaam was still leading in the number of
HIV infections and in AIDS victims, followed by Mbeya, Kagera and
Arusha regions.
</P>
<P>
About 2.2 percent of patients in Dar es Salaam hospitals were
diagnosed to be AIDS affected during 1994, climbing to about
eight percent during 1995. The figure had shot up to about 15
percent for last year, the conference paper revealed.
</P>
<P>
The statistical observation showed that one out of seven
people was HIV positive in the region.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Tanzania People's Defense Forces (TPDF) had to
a large extent, been victims of the spread of the disease, the
paper mentioned.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that many people are becoming HIV victims
by getting married to infected persons without realizing it. Many
young men and women have fallen victims to AIDS in this manner.
</P>
<P>
Certain interviewed persons suggested that the use of
equipment by different people at the same time like shaving kits
in salons may also contribute to the spread of the disease, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed shavers said that they usually shave up to 10
people with the same machine. The machine habitually inflicts
wounds on the customers, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
One shaver at the Paradise Hair-cutting Salon was quoted as
saying, "Customers usually get hurt and have wounds after making
a horizontal line behind their hair to make it look straight, so
a person can get affected."
</P>
<P>
The same effect was possible on persons who shave their beards
in salons, for the same blade is routinely applied to up to five
people, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
