<HEADLINE> Nigeria Sets New Oil Production Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has altered its oil
production target from the original 2.5 million barrels per day
by 1999 to three million barrels per day by the year 2000, the
"Business Times" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The new target was recently confirmed to oil industry players
by Bashir Dalhafu, managing director of the state-owned Nigerian
National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC), which now monopolizes the
oil industry.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria now produces about two million barrels of crude oil
per day. It is the largest oil-producing country in Africa and a
member of the Organization of Petroleum Export Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
A large proportion of Nigeria's oil production comes from
NNPC's joint ventures with foreign oil firms, including Shell,
Mobil, Agip, Texaco and Elf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
