<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Researchers Introduce Nitrogen Fixing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan researchers have
introduced a nitrogen fixing crop from Central America, and
successfully turned it over to field use, ''the New Vision''
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Frederick Alifugami, the chairperson of Ikulwe Farmers
Association under the patronage of Kawanda Agricultural
Institute, said that crotalaria ochroleuca enables soil regain
the fertility lost years ago. The upright crop with its small
root does not compete with its intercropped crops for nutrients,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The drought-tolerate crop is widely used in Central America as
a nitrogen fixer and is intercropped with maize, beans, second
season cassava or rotate with other crops.
</P>
<P>
In Ikulwe, farmers intercropped it with maize and beans.
</P>
<P>
The tropical leguminous plant with its trifoliate leaves and
yellow flowers is usually left when farmers get their harvest and
let it continue to collect more nitrogen until the next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
