<HEADLINE> Juppe: Civil Disobedience Against Immigration "Grave Act" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 17 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Alain
Juppe today hit out at the appeal for civil disobedience against a
new immigration law.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the local television RTL, Juppe said the
appeal, by some French intellectuals who are protesting the new
immigration law that requires application of certificates for
providing shelter to foreigners by French homes, "is a grave act
and it undermines the state of right and democracy."
</P>
<P>
"How can we explain to foreigners that they should respect the
laws if those important figures say that they should not respect
the law? This is an act of social disintegration at a moment when
we need social integration," Juppe said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the comparison by some French intellectuals of the
new immigration control measures with the expulsion of Jews during
the Nazi occupation and Vichy collaboration period from 1940 to
1944 "mixed up" all things.
</P>
<P>
"In France, we are a real democracy," he said, adding that the
law was voted by the deputies in the National Assembly and the
Senate under the supervision of the Constitutional Council.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the appeal for civil disobedience is a "bad
blow to our policy of integration" of foreign immigrants.
</P>
<P>
He said that registration with government for providing shelter
to foreigners, which was required as early as 1982, will let one
distinguish regular immigration and visits in France, from illegal
immigration.
</P>
<P>
Juppe said that a lot of people in France cannot differentiate
between regular immigration and illegal immigration, which he said
would indirectly help racist and xenophobic propaganda of the
National Front.  
</P>
</TEXT>
