<HEADLINE> Turkey Considers to Ban Pump-Action Shotguns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's National Security
Council has decided to discuss the issue of gun license for
pump-action shotguns because the shotguns are used mainly for
hunting people, local newspaper Daily News reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that from 1991 to 1995, 35 people were
murdered by the pump-action shotguns, which are considered to be
hunting rifles under Turkish law and do not require the owner to
obtain a gun license.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that 2,157 of the 40,000 pump-action
shotguns manufactured in Konya since 1994 were sold in that
province and the recent escalation of arms sales in Konya, a
stronghold of the Islamist Welfare Party (RP), has sparked
widespread concern in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Duzce town of Turkey has produced 24,000 hunting
rifles, mostly pump-action shotguns, and exported most of them
to earn a large income.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the office of Turkey's General Staff had
sent a letter to the Interior Ministry to ask for a ban on the
selling of these weapons in domestic markets and to revise the
regulations in favor of directing domestic suppliers towards
external markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
