<HEADLINE> Sharif Nawaz Sworn in As Pakistan New Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Nawaz Sharif was sworn in
today as Pakistan's 13th elected prime minister since its
independence in 1947.
</P>
<P>
A brief but impressive oath-taking ceremony took place at the
sprawling majestic Jinnah Hall on the fifth floor of the
Presidential House.
</P>
<P>
President Farooq Leghari administered the oath.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony, which lasted for about 25 minutes, started with
recitation from the Holy Quran following the playing of the
national anthem by a brass band.
</P>
<P>
As the ceremony began, Sharif, 46, donning "Jinnah cap", and a
national uniform -- white shalwar and dark sherwani, stood
shoulder to shoulder at attention with President Farooq Leghari on
a red carpeted platform to the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
President Leghari was the first to congratulate Sharif, who
looked confident and satisfied, with a warm handshake instantly
after the oath-taking.
</P>
<P>
The well-lighted and brilliantly-decorated great hall was
crowded with around 700 people, including the three chiefs of the
armed forces, the newly-elected speaker of the National Assembly,
outgoing caretaker prime minister and his cabinet members, foreign
diplomatic envoys as well as people from media group.
</P>
<P>
Nawaz Sharif, chief of the Pakistan Muslim League (N), secured
a vote of confidence in the National Assembly earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
Sharif is the second Pakistani leader who staged a comeback to
the top executive office after a gap of three years.
</P>
<P>
Sharif's first government was dismissed on April 18, 1993 by
the then president, Ishaq Khan. But one and a half months later,
his government was restored by the Supreme Court which held Ishaq
Khan's action unconstitutional and illegal.
</P>
<P>
The PML(N) won a landslide victory in the February 3 general
elections by bagging 135 seats in the 217-seat National Assembly.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
