<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 12:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Accuses Israel of Intending to Delay Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Vice President
Abdul-Halim Khaddam has accused Israel of intending to delay peace
talks between the two countries by trying to resume the
negotiations from "square zero," local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Khaddam made the remarks in an interview published today by
local Arabic daily Al-Rai Al-Aam.
</P>
<P>
In the interview, he said Syria had held talks with former
Israeli cabinets of Shimon Peres and Yitzhak Rabin before Binyamin
Netanyahu was elected Israeli prime minister last May.
</P>
<P>
"When the Israeli government proposes going back to square
zero, this means that we have to negotiate for a century,
because each time a new government is elected in Israel we go
back to square zero," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Syria and Israel broke off last March
following a series of suicide bombings inside Israel. Syria says
that the Labor government, which lost to Netanyahu's Likud party
in elections last May, agreed to withdraw from the Golan
heights captured from Syria in the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
"We negotiate for four years in Washington and the American
sponsor exerted enormous efforts...followed with an agreement on
some issues, most notably the withdrawal to the June 4, 1967 line
and adoption of security arrangements," Khaddam was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"It is not logically or legally justified for the Israeli
government to request going to square zero in the negotiations,"
Khaddam said.
</P>
<P>
On whether Syria has received any gesture or invitation from
Washington to resume the talks with the Israelis in light of
Netanyahu's recent talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton,
Khaddam said "so far, we have not received anything."
</P>
<P>
On Netanyahu's statement that Syria supports the resistance
against Israel in southern Lebanon, Khaddam said "Netanyahu wants
to distract the international opinion."
</P>
<P>
Khaddam recently toured the Gulf and some other Arab countries
and conveyed a letter from Syrian President Hafez al-Assad to the
Gulf leaders. The content of the letter was not released, but was
believed to have expressed Syria's stand on resuming peace talks
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that all the Gulf Cooperation Council states
supported Syria to resume the talks from where it stopped nearly
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara said Saturday in
Cairo that Israel was running away from peace and that Syria was
willing to resume peace talks as long as they start from where the
previous round left off.
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli government is the one running away from peace and
not the Syrian leadership. Syria is ready to resume negotiations
tomorrow if Israel abides by what was reached during the
previous stage," he said.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, Netanyahu said Friday "we will take note of
what took place in the talks between Syrian negotiators and the
previous (Israel) government."
</P>
<P>
But he added that "we cannot be bound by conversations or by
ideas or by speculations and suggestions and hypotheses. We can
only honor signed agreements." 
</P>
</TEXT>
