<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Rejects Israeli Assertion over "Absentee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 17 (Xinhua) - The Jordanian government Sunday
dismissed an Israeli assertion that the Jordanian-Israeli peace
treaty allows the Jewish state to continue to apply its "absentee
property law" to properties owned by Jordanians in Israel.
</P>
<P>
The comment by Jordanian Minister of Information Marwan Muasher
came in response to a statement made by the Israeli Embassy here
that Jordanians' lands and houses in Israel will continue to be
treated as absentee-owned properties under the 1950 Israeli
absentee property law, Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that Jordan was determined to press for
the return of Jordanian-owned properties in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Individual properties belonging to Jordanians prior to 1948 and
currently under custody of the Israeli "absentee-property guard" will
neither be modified or even discussed in the final phase of the
Arab-Israeli peace negotiations, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, according to the Israeli stand, the 1994 peace treaty
between Jordan and Israel does not affect the status of lands and
other individual properties and tacitly provides for the
maintaining of the status-quo.
</P>
<P>
However, Muasher said "there is a clause in the peace
treaty forbidding any discrimination (between Jordanian and
Israeli citizens) and Israel's maintaining of the current status
of absentee properties is a violation of this clause and, of the
peace treaty."
</P>
<P>
Stressing the government's commitment to ensure a just
settlement of the issue, Muasher said that while he served as
Jordan's first ambassador to Israel in 1995, the government
approached the Israeli Ministry of Foreign Affairs with an
official letter, calling for Israel's relinquishment of the
properties under custody of the absentee-property guard to their
original owners.
</P>
<P>
An absentee property committee was established in Israel in
1995. However, up to now, a complete list of all Jordanians'
properties in Israel and the occupied territories has not yet been
finalized by the committee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
