<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palace Remains Discovered in 3,000-year-old Beijing Ruins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
found the remains of palaces in some 3,000-year-old city ruins in
a southwestern suburb of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The ruins belong to the capital of the early Yan State of the
Western Zhou Dynasty (11th Century BC-771 BC). They were put in
the spotlight last year because they showed that the city of
Beijing went back 3,000 years.
</P>
<P>
It is also the only capital ever found that dates back to early
or middle Western Zhou Dynasty, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
Palaces of the Yan kings were located in the northern part of
the ruins, where beaten earth, palace wall remnants, and
large-sized drainage pipes have been found. Archaeologists say
that the city was surrounded by a 10-m-wide moat, and was square
or rectangular, with the excavated northern part of the wall being
829 meters long.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists found bronzeware with a shape and designs
similar to those found previously in imperial sites of the Western
Zhou Dynasty, and pottery similar to those found from imperial
sites of the Shang Dynasty (16th-11th Century BC), suggesting
exchanges of this northern Chinese state with the central part of
the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
