<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Current Account Deficit Surpasses 23 billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 17 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's current account
deficit skyrocketed to a record 23.7 billion U.S. dollars last
year, a whopping 165-percent increase from 8.95 billion dollars in
1995, the Bank of Korea said here today.
</P>
<P>
The central bank attributed the record current account
shortfall to a sharp decline in the growth rate of exports and a
hike in both the import of consumption goods and the invisible
trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
Comparable current account shortfall figures were 4.53 billion
dollars in 1994 and 4.53 billion dollars in 1992. South Korea
marked a current account surplus of 384.6 million dollars in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The current account comprises trade in goods and services as
well as investment income and government payments.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit in 1996 accounted for some 4.7
percent of the nation's gross national product (GNP), a bank
official said.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of the current account shortfall to GNP stood at 2.0
percent in 1995 and 1.2 percent in 1994, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
GNP refers to the total value of goods and services produced in
a nation over a particular period of time -- usually one year.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's trade deficit amounted to 15.28 billion dollars
last year, compared with shortfalls of 4.75 billion dollars in
1995 and 3.15 billion dollars in 1994 as well as a surplus of 1.86
billion dollars in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Exports grew 4.1 percent from 1995 to 128.25 billion dollars on
a free-on-board basis in 1996. The export growth rate was 31.5
percent in 1995 and 15.7 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Imports expanded 12.2 percent from 1995 to 143.53 billion
dollars in 1996. The growth rate of imports stood at 32.1 percent
in 1995 and 22.4 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country's invisible trade shortfall jumped from
3.64 billion dollars in 1995 to 7.68 billion dollars in 1996. Of
the total, travel deficit accounted for about 34 percent, or 2.6
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's foreign exchange reserves increased from 32.71
billion dollars at the end of 1995 to 33.24 billion dollars as of
the end of 1996 on an outstanding basis, according to the bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 14 More Cattle Die From Anthrax in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The worst anthrax outbreak in
the southeastern Australia state of Victoria was expected to
spread further this week with the onset of more hot and dry
weather, the state government said today.
</P>
<P>
A total of 119 cattle have died, up from Sunday's 105, while 59
properties are under quarantine, and 25,000 cattle have been
vaccinated to try to contain the disease, which broke out in the
Tatura-Stanhope area on January 26.
</P>
<P>
Principal veterinary officer of the Department of Natural
Resources and Environment Terry Thomas said that specialists were
investigating whether flies biting infected stock were spreading
the disease.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, "I don't think we have got a satisfactory
explanation yet for such a big outbreak on so many properties,
other possibilities were movement of machinery, humans and stock,
the weather and water."
</P>
<P>
Victorian Deputy Premier Pat McNamara said in the state
cabinet, "It looks like we are going to have those hot and dry
conditions for the rest of the week, so I think we could probably
anticipate that we are going to have some further incidence of
stock dying".
</P>
<P>
Anthrax causes rapid death in cattle, sheep and goats when they
eat contaminated soil or feed, but health officials have stressed
the outbreak poses no threat to public health or safety.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
