<HEADLINE> Sharif Asks Negotiations With India on Kashmir Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's prime
minister-elect Nawaz Sharif today reiterated his offer to the
neighboring India for "a peaceful negotiated settlement" of the
Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan firmly believed in good-neighborly relations and it
was the time for India to come to the negotiating table and
resolve "the pending core issue," Sharif said after securing a
vote of confidence in the 217-member National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
He said that India must accept that the unresolved Kashmir
issue is the major hindrance in the way of normalization of
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"It's the time to try to do it," Sharif said, hoping that India
would reciprocate in the same manner.
</P>
<P>
Normalization of relations between Pakistan and India was also
in the best interest of peace and tranquillity in South Asia, said
Sharif, who is to be sworn in later in the day as the new prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
On the Pakistan-US relations, Sharif said, these have
consolidated over the past and efforts would continue to further
improve these bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
He said, Pakistan's relations with the Muslim world have always
remained cordial and substantive, and would improve and strengthen
further in the time ahead.  
</P>
</TEXT>
