<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Fighting Local Protectionism in Law-enforcement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 17 (Xinhua) -- China's central government
will launch a national campaign to halt local protectionism and
departmentalism in law enforcement, in the second quarter of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Local protectionism and departmentalism in law-enforcement have
become widespread and serious and have evoked strong responses from
many parts of society, according to an article in "Outlook"
Magazine published here today.
</P>
<P>
The article said that a small number of Party and government
officials support or work with departments and individuals to
protect local and departmental interests by devious means, it said.
</P>
<P>
Some law-enforcement organs compete with each other to handle
lawsuits to protect the interests of the party involved in their
own region. Some lawyers and notaries in some regions have
violated professional ethics, engaging in unfair legal practices.
</P>
<P>
Driven by local interest, some financial and administrative
departments kept the judiciary from enforcing the law in a fair
way. Some departments and personnel have used ingenious methods to
meddle with or even resist law-enforcement personnel in the
performance of their duties, the article added.
</P>
<P>
The Protectionism in law-enforcement is harmful to the
socialist market-oriented economy, China's four modernization
drive, and to the socialist legal system, the article said.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that protectionism in law-enforcement must be
thoroughly eradicated, the article said party committees and
governments at all levels should take the lead in safeguarding the
dignity of the law and judicial departments should treat
protectionism in law-enforcement as a major problem in the fight
against corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPC, Government Decision on Health Reform And Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) and the State Council calls for
still better work to be done in the country's health care reforms
and development.
</P>
<P>
According to the decision by the CPC Central Committee and the
State Council released here today, China will improve its health
care system by the year 2000 to meet its goal of "Health Care for
Everyone" and to improve general public health.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, the decision says, this system is expected to raise
China to the level of the developed countries or the advanced
levels in developing countries in public health.
</P>
<P>
The system includes health care services, medical insurance,
and enforcing public health laws. The health policy will focus on
rural areas and preventative medicine, Western and traditional
Chinese medicine, science and technology, getting all of society
involved in health work, and improving people's health to serve
the socialist modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
The health policy of the new period will focus on rural areas
and preventative work, pay more attention to both Western and
traditional Chinese medicine, rely on scientific and technological
progress, aroused the involvement from whole society in the health
work, and help improve the people's health and to serve the
socialist modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
Health work is a public activity involving government policy
and should be coordinated with the national economy and social
development. It urges government at all levels to increase input
in the field of public health and to get society to raise funds to
improve work in the field, the decision notes.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century, overall expenditures on health work
are expected to account for five percent of total GDP.
</P>
<P>
The cardinal principles for future health reforms and
development are as follows:
</P>
<P>
Adhering to the the general purpose of serving the people,
handling properly the relationship between social benefits and
cost, and making social benefit top priority;
</P>
<P>
Making efforts mainly to improve people's health and set
essential health requirements;
</P>
<P>
Making rational disposition of medical resources, improving
quality and efficiency of service, focusing on rural areas and
preventative medicine and traditional Chinese medicine to
gradually narrow the gap between different regions.
</P>
<P>
Setting up more state-owned and collectively-run medical
services and or getting supplementary privately-run services;
</P>
<P>
Strengthen international cooperation and exchanges, learning
from technological advances and managerial experience abroad;
</P>
<P>
Improving the moral and professional conduct of medical
personnel and perfecting their professionalism.
</P>
<P>
The whole Party and all of society are asked to pay greater
attention to health care and to protect and improve public
health. An important goal of socialist modernization is improving
the nation's general health conditions and to let everyone enjoy
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
In the 47 years following the birth of the new China and
especially in the past 18 years since the launching of the
country's reform and opening-up, major achievements have been made
in the field of medicine, with the average life span rising
dramatically from 35 to 70. The infant mortality rate has also
dropped significantly to 31.4 from as many as 200 per thousand in
1949.
</P>
<P>
Health work in China, however, still leaves much to be desired,
it says, and Party committees and government at all levels should
improve leadership in the field and increase reforms.
</P>
<P>
The next 15 years will be a crucial period in China's socialist
modernization drive, and public health provides a challenge, it
concludes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPC, Government Decision on Health Reform and Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The objective of health care reform is precisely to increase
the vitality of the cause of public health and give full scope to
medical institutions and individual health workers, and keep
improving both the quality and efficiency of health service.
</P>
<P>
To comply with the socialist market economy and follow what
guides the development of public health, a new mechanism full of
vitality should be established. Employee medical insurance
combined with social welfare should provide a basic medical
guarantee for all urban workers.
</P>
<P>
Medical costs will be shared by the State, the employer, and
the employee, in reasonable proportions, according to the decision.
</P>
<P>
A mechanism that provides for both constraints on doctors and
on patients should be built to halt the fast growth of medical
expenses.
</P>
<P>
The institutions and medical personnel are urged to take part
in medical reforms and to make an effort to cut waste of medical
resources, and government departments should do a better job in
making up for deficiencies in medical care.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000 all cities and towns will basically have a
medical insurance system, and other kinds of supplementary medical
insurance should be encouraged, it said.
</P>
<P>
While the present unban medical service system should be
reformed, institutions at the grass-roots level should provide
basic medical services such as family planning and health
education, and health services for women, infants, the disabled,
and the elderly.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, major hospitals in urban areas will mainly deal with
emergencies and serious medical problems and play an important
role in scientific and technological research and training medical
personnel.
</P>
<P>
Controls will be tightened on private medical businesses and
other medical services. Reforms should include public health
institutions and a system of hospital director responsibility to
expand their power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
