<HEADLINE> Japan Plans to Exchange Navy Personnel with Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Japan plans to have an
exchange program for navy officers and other personnel with
Malaysia to promote relations between the two navies, Japanese
Maritime Self-Defense Force Chief of Staff Admiral Kazuya
Natsukawa said today.
</P>
<P>
He said the Malaysian army and air force had already sent their
officers for such programs, so now "it is the navy's turn."
</P>
<P>
The present relationship between the navies of the two
countries was confined to personal contacts between senior
officers, he told reporters after his talks with Royal Malaysian
Navy (RMN) Chief Ahmad Ramli Mohamed Nor here.
</P>
<P>
Japanese navy ships and officers have visited Malaysia in the
past few years to promote better ties, he said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the current bilateral relations as good, he said
both countries share similar views on regional security and feel
the need for better relations and confidence-building measures.
</P>
<P>
On joint naval exercise with the RMN, he said it was difficult
for Japan to take part in due to constitutional constraint.
Japan's post-war constitution renounces war and the use of force,
but allows the country to maintain ground, air and maritime
self-defense forces.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese navy chief, who arrived here Sunday for a four-day
visit with a five-member delegation, also called on Malaysian
Defense Minister Syed Hamid Albar here.  
</P>
</TEXT>
