<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Noted Woman Physicist of Chinese Origin Dies in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Well-known American nuclear
physicist of Chinese origin, Wu Chien Shiung, died of an
apoplectic stroke here around noon on Sunday at the age of 84.
</P>
<P>
Born in May, 1912, in China's Jiangsu Province, she came to
study at the University of California in 1936 and served as a
professor of physics there later.
</P>
<P>
She earned her doctor's degree in physics at the University of
California in 1940 and a number of other universities including
Princeton, Yale and Harvard.
</P>
<P>
After 1944, Wu worked at the University of Colombia and made
outstanding achievements in the study of nuclear physics.
</P>
<P>
In the 1950s, she proved the law of parity conservation created
by Chen Ning Yang and Tsung Dao Lee, for which Yang and Lee were
awarded the Nobel Prize in physics.
</P>
<P>
Wu was elected as one of the first foreign academicians of the
Chinese Academy of Science in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army Wounds Rebel Commander </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan army wounded
Colonel Moses Gala, commander of the West Nile Bank Front (WNBF)
rebels, placing this rebel group in great difficulty, "the New
Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Gala was injured last Wednesday in a clash with the government
troops when the WNBF rebels tried to enter northwestern Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The government troops foiled the raid and pursued the rebels
up to 13 kilometers into Zaire and killed 56 rebels. Earlier
reports put death toll in the clash at 27.
</P>
<P>
Gala was then admitted in a hospital in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The WNBF rebels now are sandwiched between Tutsi rebels in
Zaire and Ugandan troops in western Uganda, and its formerly
2,000 members might have been greatly reduced, observers here
say.
</P>
<P>
In northern district of Kitgum, Uganda army discovered 29
anti-tank mines in a hunt for hideout of Lord's Resistance Army
last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The government troops found another batch of 5,400 rounds of
ammunition in the district earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
In another northern district of Gulu, about 20 LRA rebels
killed three civilians and abducted another 13 last friday.
</P>
<P>
In western Kasese district, local defense units patrol day and
night. The army and local defense units sealed all roads to
prevent Allied Democratic Forces' rebels to escape.
</P>
<P>
Major Kalyoma, commander of local defense units, predicted the
rebellion in the district will be eradicated by the combined
efforts of the government troops and local defense units. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
