<HEADLINE> Desert Dust Sweeps Through Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 17 (Xinhua) -- A thick belt of dust from the
Sahara desert has swept through Uganda and several other
sub-Saharan countries, causing hazy weather, reported the New
Vision daily today.
</P>
<P>
The haze is also covering Kenya, Tanzania, Central African
Republic and Sudan, experts in the meteorologic department here
were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The phenomenon began last December and is predicted to last
until March 21 this year when the sun crosses the equator from
the southern hemisphere to the north.
</P>
<P>
The experts said, "at the moment there is high pressure in
Europe. It extends a ridge and passes through the Arabian
Peninsula, Libya and Sudan. it intensifies, picks up dust and
sends it to low pressure areas like Uganda in the South of the
Sahara."
</P>
<P>
However, the experts warned that environmental degradation,
especially deforestation is a cause of the current dry spell.
"When we used to have a thick Mabira forest near Kampala we used
to have a lot of rain over Kampala due to the high content of
moisture." 
</P>
</TEXT>
