<HEADLINE> Philippine Defense Chief Dismisses Coup Speculation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Defense Secretary
Renato de Villa today allayed fears that a military coup plotted
by President Fidel Ramos' backers is in the offing in the light of
their current moves to extend Ramos' term.
</P>
<P>
The defense chief was reacting to a statement made Sunday by
Senator Raul Roco that Ramos and his backers will use force if all
other means to extend his term, such as amending the constitution,
would be unavailing.
</P>
<P>
In an interview, De Villa said a military coup similar to those
launched by rightist soldiers during the Aquino regime will not
happen anymore.
</P>
<P>
"In so far as military coups are concerned or plots coming from
the direction of the Armed Forces, I think that is history," De
Villa said. "I believe it will not be repeated in our time
anymore."
</P>
<P>
Roco, who has already made known his intention to run for the
presidency in the 1998 presidential elections, made the accusation
following an admission from Executive Secretary Ruben Torres that
the ruling Lakas-NUCD leadership is in favor of a charter change
to extend the term of Ramos.
</P>
<P>
On February 8, Ramos himself said he wants a charter change to
clarify the separation of powers between the three branches of
government and to clip the power of the Supreme Court following
its decision to void the bid of a Malaysian firm for the purchase
of Manila Hotel.
</P>
<P>
Roco observed that once the Supreme Court, Congress and the
executive branch are caught in a gridlock on the issue of charter
change, force will be promoted as the only option to keep the
country moving.
</P>
<P>
Several days after Ramos openly expressed his desire to change
the constitution, the president went further by vetoing a
provision of the 1997 national budget which bans any budget fund
for a national plebiscite to amend the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Although Ramos repeatedly said he has no intention of extending
his term by changing the charter, his recent moves have been
strongly criticized by the opposition and those perspective
presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
They said that Ramos' ruling Lakas-NUCD party will push for the
extension of his term if the door is open to amending the current
constitution which provides for a single six-year term for the
president.
</P>
<P>
Against such a background, Torres, a close aide to Ramos and a
senior official of the Lakas party, admitted Saturday that his
party really favored an extension of Ramos' term because "six
years are too short for a good president."  
</P>
</TEXT>
