<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 08:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Disappointed with Turkish-Iraqi Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has found it still
tough to benefit itself from trade with Iraq although the
oil-for-food agreement has been put into effect, local
newspaper Daily News said today.
</P>
<P>
Following the implementation of the agreement, which was
reached on May 20, 1996 between the U.N. and Iraq, nearly 400
Turkish firms proposed trade deals with the Iraqi side, but only
10 of them have reached agreements so far.
</P>
<P>
According to the terms of the oil-for-food agreement, all
contracts must be submitted to the U.N. Sanctions Committee for
approval, and so far only five deals worth 25 million U.S. dollars
have been approved.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted an Iraqi official as saying that the
situation was caused by the high prices proposed by Turkish
firms, saying this made many Turkish companies uncompetitive.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official said that port services offered by the
Turkish side were also expensive.
</P>
<P>
However, some Turkish traders denied this claim, adding that
Iraq was using other transportation means because of Turkey's
policy on northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been the base for U.S.-led Operation Provide
Comfort (OPC) aimed at providing air protection for the Iraqi
Kurds living in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government has claimed that this mission was an
infringement on Iraq's sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food agreement ratified by the United Nations
allows Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil over six
months to buy food and medicine badly needed by the Iraqis, who
have suffered from the U.N. sanctions imposed on Baghdad since
its invasion of Kuwait in August 1990.
</P>
<P>
It was anticipated that at least half of the exported Iraqi
oil would be transported through Turkey via the
Kirkuk-Yumurtalik pipeline, making it possible for Turkey to earn
transit fees up to 50 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Over the past six years, Turkey was estimated to have
suffered a loss of 27 billion dollars from the U.N. sanctions
imposed on Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
