<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zaire Civilians, Soldiers Flee To Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Up to 1,500 civilians
are crossing Lake Tanganyika daily to escape rebel advances in
eastern Zaire, joined by smaller numbers of ragged Zairean
soldiers, reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
There are already more than 15,000 Zairean refugees in camps
around Kigoma on the eastern shore of the lake in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The latest group of 50 Zairean soldiers, demoralized,
ill-equipped and wearing tattered uniforms, reached Kigoma last
Friday, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday 161 Zairean soldiers, heavily armed with guns,
grenades and ammunition, arrived in Kigoma by boat.
</P>
<P>
Up to 1,500 Zaireans a day have been crossing Lake Tanganyika
to seek refuge in Tanzania over the last three weeks, the reports
added.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania had several hundred thousand refugees from other
central African crises living on its soil last year.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all of the more than half a million Rwandan refugees in
Tanzania returned home last December.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 200,000 refugees from Burundi are still in
Tanzania, some from as far back as 1972, the reports noted.
</P>
<P>
Food and other supplies are short in Kalemie, the main Zairean
port on Lake Tanganyika, and a cholera outbreak in the area has
killed more than 300 people in the last few weeks, arriving
refugees told reporters. 
</P>
