<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Needs "New Start": Sharif </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's prime
minister-elect Nawaz Sharif said today his party would bring the
country "a new start" and do its utmost to overcome problems
facing the country.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan "needs a new start" after 50 years of its existence,
Sharif said after winning a vote of confidence in the National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The 217-seat assembly cast 177 votes for Sharif, chief of the
Pakistan Muslim League (N). Former defense minister Aftab Shaban
Mirani of Benazir Bhutto's Pakistan People's Party secured only 16
votes.
</P>
<P>
The PML(N) should not rest content with the victory of the
February 3 elections, instead it should spend every minute to the
development of Pakistan and better the life standard of the
people, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sharif is to be sworn in as the country's 8th prime minister
since 1988 in a ceremony to be held later in the day in the
Presidential House. President Farooq Leghari will administer the
oath.
</P>
<P>
Around 700 people, including the three chiefs of the armed
forces, the outgoing caretaker prime minister and his cabinet
members, outgoing provincial chief ministers, governors and
members of the two houses of parliament will be present in the
sprawling majestic hall of the fifth floor of the Presidency.
</P>
<P>
After being sworn-in as the executive head of the country,
Sharif will address the house, in which he would explain the
priorities of his government.
</P>
<P>
Sharif's PML(N) has won a landslide victory in the February 3
elections held as a result of the dismissal of the Benazir
government by winning a two-thirds majority in the 217-seat
National Assembly while the PPP has only scored 17 seats.
</P>
</TEXT>
