<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Urge to Reform Science Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEATTLE, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Scientists and educators from
developed as well as developing countries today unanimously called
for a radical reform of science education at high schools.
</P>
<P>
Professors from China, Germany, Turkey and South Africa
attending a 5-day seminar on science education here pointed out
that science education at high schools has not drawn enough
attention from various governments and the general public.
</P>
<P>
Emphasizing the importance of science and mathematics for any
education toward the 21st century, Bruce Alberts, president of
U.S. National Academy of Science, regretted that teachers in the
United States "are not teaching science, but teaching science
words."
</P>
<P>
He said that part of the problem is the quality of teachers,
citing the fact that in 1990 only two teachers out of 1,000 in San
Francisco schools had majored in science.
</P>
<P>
They said that high school teachers and students only pursue
high marks, instead of teaching or learning knowledge and skills,
which they said are crucial to their future career and even the
rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
"A high capacity for abstract, conceptual thinking "should be
the purpose of high school science education, said one of the
participants in the discussions. Students should learn "how to
solve real-world problems."
</P>
<P>
Alberts said high school students also need the ability to work
easily and well with others and the skill required to resolve
conflict that arise with colleagues.
</P>
<P>
Many speakers offered suggestions on revising textbooks as well
as the method of teaching. Alberts said that science education
should be "hands-on, inquiry-based experiences" and communication
skills and problem-solving skills should be emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Learning from a teacher who serves as a source of all knowledge
should be replaced by a much more active and noisy classroom, in
which the teacher serves as a wise "coach" to encourage student
investigation and student problem solving, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
