<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharif Wins Vote of Confidence in NA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Nawaz Sharif today was
unanimously elected Pakistan's new prime minister after winning a
vote of confidence in the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, Chief of the Pakistan Muslim League (N), won the vote
of confidence by 177 votes in favor in the 217-member National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Sharif is to be sworn in as the country's 8th prime minister in
a ceremony held later in the day in the Presidential House.
President Farooq Leghari will administer the oath.
</P>
<P>
Aftab Shaban Mirani, former defense minister and candidate of
the Pakistan People's Party for the post of the prime minister won
only 16 votes.
</P>
<P>
Around 700 people, including the three chiefs of the armed
forces, outgoing caretaker prime minister and his cabinet members,
outgoing provincial chief ministers, governors and members of the
two houses of parliament will be present at the oath-taking
ceremony to be held in the majestic hall on the fifth floor of the
Presidential House.
</P>
<P>
After his election as the executive head of the country, Sharif
will address the house, in which he would explain the priorities
of his government.
</P>
<P>
Sharif is the second Pakistani leader who is staging a comeback
to the top executive office after a gap of three years.
</P>
<P>
Sharif's first government was dismissed on April 18, 1993, by
the then President Ishaq Khan. But one and a half months later,
his government was restored by the Supreme Court which held Ishaq
Khan's action unconstitutional and illegal.
</P>
<P>
Then a war of mutual destruction ensued between the two. It
ended with the resignation of both in July, 1993, as a result of a
deal brokered by the army to end the country's political chaos.
</P>
<P>
Before Sharif, it was Benazir Bhutto, the PPP Chairperson, who
became prime minister twice in a short span of time. She first
assumed the premiership in 1988 and was dismissed in 1990 by Ishaq
Khan.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, Benazir became prime minister again. But she was
sacked for the second time by President Leghari on November 5 last
year on charges of extra-judicial killing, corruption and misrule.
</P>
<P>
Sharif's PML(N) has won a landslide victory in the February 3
elections by winning a two-thirds majority in the 217-seat
National Assembly while the PPP has only scored 17 seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
