<HEADLINE> India's Congress Party to Extend "Issue-based" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 17 (Xinhua) -- India's Congress Party on
Sunday night decided to extend "issue-based" support to the United
Front minority government instead of "unconditional" support
offered so far, the National Herald reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Congress Working Committee (CWC), the supreme
decision-making body of the Congress Party, made this decision
after a five-hour-long in-depth meeting on the party's relations
with the United Front government headed by Prime Minister H.D.
Deve Gowda.
</P>
<P>
The committee also authorized the party's President Sitaram
Kesri to talk to the leaders of the 14-party United Front and
thereafter take appropriate steps.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters after the meeting, party spokesman V.N.
Gadgil said the message was loud and clear that the Congress Party
was not afraid of facing a mid-term poll, if needed, and that the
United Front government "can not take our support for granted."
</P>
<P>
The Congress Party's outside support is crucial for the
government of the United Front which occupies only 190 out of the
545 seats in the House of People (the lower house of parliament).
 
</P>
