<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Stresses Balanced European Role in NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi said on Sunday that the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO)'s eastward expansion plan should be transparent and allow
"full participation of all members".
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with visiting United States Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, Prodi also agreed with Albright on the
need of Russia's "constructive and responsible involvement" in
NATO's enlargement into central and eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Prodi's statement was in response to a French plan for an April
summit by five nations, excluding Italy, to discuss Russia's role
in NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
France proposed that France, Germany, Britain, the United
States and Russia meet before a scheduled summit of the 16 NATO
members in July in Madrid, Spain, which is to consider NATO's
restructuring and its relations with Russia in the post-Cold War
era, and its first recruitment of new members.
</P>
<P>
While acknowledging that the transatlantic links within the
alliance should be reaffirmed, Prodi said that Europe had a
"growing" need to map out its own security and defense identity,
according to a statement issued by the prime minister's office.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who newly took over the office of the U.S. State
Department, said she appreciated "Italy's constructive role in the
Balkans and the Mediterranean".
</P>
<P>
Prodi's view of a balanced European role in NATO expansion was
echoed by Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini, who, addressing a joint
news conference with Albright, said Italy "does not accept the
idea of a few countries meeting to discuss ideas that affect all
the countries in NATO".
</P>
<P>
Earlier on the day, Defense Minister Beniamino Andreatta said
he had sought to impress upon the U.S. state secretary in their
talks the need to strike a balance between North and South.
</P>
<P>
Andreatta said the enlargement must not merely reflect "the
geopolitics of middle Europe", but that of Europe as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that NATO is no longer the same as it was in the Cold
War, Albright told the Italian defense minister she was chiefly
concerned with security architecture rather than territorial
defense, Andreatta said.
</P>
<P>
In a Saturday interview with a French newspaper, Albright said
that a Europe within NATO should not be "perceived as being
directed against the Russians", and talks on creating a new
NATO-Russian charter were under way, which would set up a joint
council.
</P>
<P>
Moscow has been firm in opposing a NATO expansion to its
border, saying that would endanger Russia's national security and
risk a divided Europe.
</P>
<P>
Italy was the first stop of a round-the-world journey by
Albright, which will also take her to Germany, France, Britain,
Belgium, Russia, and Asian countries of South Korea, Japan and
China before ending on February 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Tea Standards Meeting Opens In Colombo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The 17th Meeting of the
Technical Committee of the International Standards Organization
(ISO) opened here today.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from Britain, Indonesia, Kenya, India, Germany,
Poland, the United States and Sri Lanka participated the opening
ceremony of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka Minister of Public Administration, Home Affairs and
Plantation Industries Ratnasiri Wickramanayake said at the
ceremony that the entire world is moving towards the
standardization of products. Tea producers and exporters cannot
ignore the global trends in the commodity and product markets.
</P>
<P>
He noted that both public sector and private sector
institutions need to respond quickly to these changing situations
and successfully work towards the challenges of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The Minister said that the International Standards Institute
can play a central role in upgrading the product quality and the
standards of teas that are being offered to the market.
</P>
<P>
Some of the important items included in the agenda for the
meeting are substances characteristic of Green tea and Black tea,
standards relating to classification and grading of tea by
particle. Size analysis and specification for tea sacks are
expected to be finalized at this meeting, according to organizers
of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The ISO Technical Committee is responsible for the development
of International Standards relating to the tea trade which are now
 increasingly used for quality assurance and regulatory control
activities in the international tea trade, they pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Many technical issues relating to quality, grading, analysis,
packaging and transport of tea which would have a direct bearing
on the Sri Lankan tea trade will come up for discussion at the
3-day meeting, they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
