<HEADLINE> Australian PM Ends Visit to NZ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
left here this afternoon at the end of a three-day visit which has
created plenty of goodwill but made no specific deals between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
He held formal talks with officials of the NZ government this
morning, including Prime Minister Jim Bolger. The talks covered a
range of issues without any formal decisions made.
</P>
<P>
Bolger said after the talks that the ties between the two
countries have never been better, and Howard said he is here to
make sure that the two countries are to maintain the good
relationship.
</P>
<P>
There are now no outstanding issues between the two neighbors
after Howard became Prime Minister last year. But it is understood
Howard wants to persuade NZ to commit more money on defense by
buying two more Australian-made frigates.
</P>
<P>
However, he told reporters after the meeting that "the question
how much NZ spends on defense, or social security or anything else
is a matter for New Zealanders" and "I don't come here to give
public lectures."
</P>
<P>
To voice its opposition to buying the frigates which NZ has
already bought two, pressure group Just Defense unfurled a large
banner near the parliament this morning where the talks were held,
 reading "Mr. Howard, NZrs don't need your useless frigates."
</P>
<P>
NZ has also made no comprise on Australia's plan to extend the
stand-down period for immigrants applying for benefits in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
Now, New Zealanders living in Australia have a six-month
stand-down period before they can collect the dole, but Australia
wants to extend that to two years.
</P>
<P>
Howard also met NZ Deputy Prime Minister Winston Peters this
morning and Opposition leader Helen Clark before flying home.
</P>
</TEXT>
