<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soap Bubble Geometry Presented at U.S. Science Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEATTLE, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Could the familiar soap bubble
be a topic at a prestigious science conference?
</P>
<P>
Yes. It is one of the topics at the ongoing annual meeting of
the American Association for the Advancement of Sciences (AAAS)
with more than 5,000 attendees.
</P>
<P>
"Art, bubbles, crystals, domes, geometry in the world around
you" is listed among the 143 topics on which more than 1,000
speakers make their presentations.
</P>
<P>
Soap bubble involves a century-old conjecture -- the Double
Bubble Conjecture
</P>
<P>
Frank Morgan, a professor of mathematics with Williams College
in Massachusetts, explained that soap bubbles try to minimize
area, and it is a famous theorem that a sphere - a single round
soap bubble - provides the least-area way to enclose a given
volume of air.
</P>
<P>
When two soap bubbles come together, they produce a
double consisting of two partial spheres and a separating
surface. The conjecture says that this standard shape is indeed
the least-area way to enclose and separate the two given volumes
of air.
</P>
<P>
The single soap bubble theorem, which says that it provides the
most efficient way to enclose a single prescribed volume, was
celebrated by the ancient Greeks and finally proved mathematically
by H.A. Schwartz in 1884. But the double bubble shape continues to
stump mathematicians.
</P>
<P>
Last year, two Californian mathematicians, Joel Hass and Roger
Schlafly, finally cracked the double bubble conjecture by
computations. They proved that the standard double bubble of equal
areas has less surface area than any alternative.
</P>
<P>
The two mathematicians' proof depended on earlier undergraduate
research at Williams College by 12 students. They proved the
planar version of the Double Bubble Conjecture, according to
Prof. Morgan. They did it in 1990 in a research geometry group.
</P>
<P>
The equal volumes case of the Double Bubble Conjecture has been
proved but the unequal volumes case remains open, Morgan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nawaz Sharif to Be Sworn in as New Pak PM Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Chief of the Pakistan Muslim
League(N) Nawaz Sharif is to be sworn in as the country's new
prime minister after winning a vote of confidence in the National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The National Assembly is to meet today at 9.00 a.m. to elect
the new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Elahi Bakhsh Soomro, the newly-elected Speaker of the National
Assembly, will preside over the session.
</P>
<P>
Sharif and former defense minister Aftab Shaban Mirani from the
Pakistan People's Party filed their nomination papers to the
Secretary General of the National Assembly through their
representatives on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The winner of the contest will be sworn in later in the day at
a ceremony to be held at the Presidential House. President Farooq
Leghari will administer the oath.
</P>
<P>
Around 700 people, including the three chiefs of the armed
forces, outgoing caretaker prime minister, his cabinet members,
outgoing provincial chief ministers, governors and members of the
two houses of parliament will be present at the occasion.
</P>
<P>
Sharif, whose PML(N) holds a two-thirds majority in the
217-seat National Assembly, is certain to occupy the office of the
prime minister for the second time since 1993.
</P>
<P>
It is most likely that Sharif, who is also the PML(N)'s
parliamentary leader, will win the support of more than 175
National Assembly members.
</P>
<P>
The PML(N) already enjoys the strength of 135 seats in the
National Assembly besides the clear-cut support of its allied
parties including the Awami (People's) National Party (ANP) and
the Mohajir Qaumi Movement (MQM).
</P>
<P>
National Assembly members from the Federal-Administered Tribal
Areas as well as those belonging to the minorities are also likely
to favor Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The election of the prime minister is likely to be unanimous,
in view of the gesture shown by Benazir Bhutto and her party,
during the election of the Speaker and the Deputy Speaker on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The PPP, who bagged only 17 seats in the February 3 elections
in the National Assembly, probably will withdraw its candidate as
it did in the election of the Speaker and Deputy Speaker of the
National Assembly on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
After his election as the executive head of the country, Sharif
will address the house, in which he would explain the priorities
of his government.
</P>
<P>
Benazir Bhutto, who is likely to be elected as opposition
leader, may also address the house.
</P>
<P>
Sharif is the second Pakistani leader who is staging a comeback
to the top executive office after a gap of three years.
</P>
<P>
Sharif's government was dismissed on April 18, 1993 by the then
President Ishaq Khan. But one and a half months later, his
government was restored by the Supreme Court which held Ishaq
Khan's action unconstitutional and illegal.
</P>
<P>
Then a war of mutual destruction ensued between the two. It
ended with the resignation of both in July 1993, as a result of a
deal brokered by the army to end political chaos.
</P>
<P>
Before Sharif, it was Benazir who became prime minister twice
in a short span of time. She assumed this office in 1988 and was
dismissed in 1990 by Ishaq Khan. She again became prime minister
in 1993 and was sacked again by President Leghari on November 5
last year on charges of extra-judicial killings, corruption and
misrule.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
