<HEADLINE> Indonesia Brands ASEM Political Talks "Ineffective" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian foreign minister
Ali Alatas has criticized last Saturday's Asian-Europe meeting
(ASEM) in Singapore for attempting to discuss major political
issues in a cramped one-day agenda.
</P>
<P>
"How is it possible to discuss substantive political issues in
one day when the U.N. does it in three months?" Alatas told
Indonesian journalists Sunday, according to an Antara news agency
report today.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is "reluctant" to address substantive political
issues in ASEM as the exercise is "ineffective," and undermines
the discussion of "other matters of importance," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that Indonesia's criticism of ASEM is shared by other
Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
Alatas pointed out that "there seems to be an impression among
European countries that Asia is shy of discussing political issues
in ASEM."
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's principle of not engaging in the discussion of
major political issues is based on the statement made by the
chairman of the first ASEM in Bangkok last year, which read that
"all dialogs should articulate issues that have been mutual agreed
upon with the aim of fostering mutual understanding and
friendship."
</P>
<P>
Alatas emphasized that the Bangkok statement "is the principle
under which all dialogs should be held in ASEM."
</P>
<P>
One of the European countries which had openly mentioned
Indonesia's reluctance to discuss crucial political issues was
Portugal as it had from the beginning expected a thorough
discussion on the East Timor issue.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, an Indonesian delegate to the ASEM said ASEAN (the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations) was united in opposing any
discussion on East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, Portugal and the U.N. are involved in the annual
tripartite talks on East Timor, which have been going on for the
past five years under the auspices of the world body's secretary
general. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
