<HEADLINE> Romania's Fidatov Keeps IAAF Cross-Country Lead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Romania's Elena Fidatov
Sunday won the 4.8 kilometers women's race in Diekrch, Luxembourg,
keeping her dominance of the International Amateur Athletic
Federation (IAAF) World Cross Challenge series.
</P>
<P>
Fidatov, 36, finished in 15 minutes 50 seconds to record her
sixth win of the series.
</P>
<P>
But she just held off Swiss teenager Anita Weyermann in a
furious sprint over the final 200 meters of the treacherous
course, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Weyermann, the 1996 world junior 3,000 meters champion,
finished second in 15:52, followed by South Africa's Colleen de
Reuck in 16:02.
</P>
<P>
Fidatov continues to lead the overall cross challenge rankings
with 100 points. Ethiopia's Gete Wami, the reigning world
champion, did not race on Sunday but remains second with 88 points.
</P>
<P>
In the 10.2-meter men's race, Kenya's Bernard Barmasai narrowly
beat Morocco's Mohammed Mourit for his second victory of the
season with a time of 30:41.
</P>
<P>
Mourit was second in 30:43. The third went to Germany's Dieter
Baumann in 30:59.
</P>
<P>
Barmasai's win puts him in the lead in the men's world cross
challenge standings with 72 points. Britain's Keith Cullen, who
was second earlier on Sunday in Chiba, Japan, stands second with
67 points.
</P>
<P>
The world cross challenge is a 12-race series and has a 25,000
U.S. dollars first prize for both the men's and women's
winners. The next race is Nairobi, Kenya on February 22. 
</P>
