<HEADLINE> Romania Cracks Down on Poor-Quality or Pseudo Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Romania scored remarkable
achievements in cracking down on poor-quality and pseudo products
to protect the interests and rights of consumers in the past year.
</P>
<P>
The Bureau of Consumers Protection under the government has
inspected markets across the country for 56,000 times and imposed
on illegal businessmen a total penalty of 56 billion Lev (about
11.4 million U.S. dollar).
</P>
<P>
The bureau also seized poor-quality goods worth 886 billion Lev
(about 1.8 billion dollars), of which 52 percent were imported.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the country's markets have been flooded with
poor-quality and fake goods, especially false famous-brand foreign
wines and liquor, Romania's Libera newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the bureau seized more than 4,000 litres of such
wines and liquor in the capital city of Bucharest alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
