<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baht Devaluation Won't Help Exports: Thai Banker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 17 (Xinhua) -- A leading Thai banker believes
that Thailand's economic structure has changed so much that a
devaluation of the baht would not greatly benefit exports.
</P>
<P>
Olarn Chaipravat, chairman of the Thai Bankers' Association,
said at the weekend that in 1981 and 1984 the baht was devalued,
making Thailand's main exports, agricultural products, cheaper.
</P>
<P>
However, industrial goods have today become the country's major
foreign currency-earner, and 43 percent of the raw materials and
content of manufactured exports are imported.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, devaluation would increase the costs for
manufacturers and make their exports more expensive, Olarn said.
</P>
<P>
"The result would be that Thailand would lost its
competitiveness. this is why I say we cannot devalue our baht --
not at all," he said.
</P>
<P>
In recently months the baht has been depreciating against the
surging US dollar and foreign traders are speculating that the
Thai government will have to devalue the baht to boost exports.
Thailand's exports declined by 0.1 percent last year, the first
drop for decades.
</P>
<P>
Besides the adverse impact on exports, devaluation would
increase the country's external debt, according to Olarn.
</P>
<P>
Preserving the value of the baht is the top priority, Olarn
said, adding that the Bank of Thailand and the Finance Ministry
would have to fight to the end, drawing on all their foreign
reserves.
</P>
<P>
If Thailand devalued the baht as the foreign traders wanted,
the Thai economy would collapse, Olarn claimed.
</P>
<P>
In the last few months, there have been rumors about the
possible devaluation of the baht, but the Bank of Thailand has
repeatedly denied.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
