<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Italy Agree on NATO Eastward Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Visiting U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and her Italian counterpart Lamberto Dini said
today that the NATO expansion should remain in process without
spoiling the relationship with Russia.
</P>
<P>
To avoid being in opposition to Russia is one of the goals of a
new NATO, said Albright, who started in Italy her maiden overseas
trip as the first woman top diplomat of Washington.
</P>
<P>
During her 11-day trip to Rome, Bonn, Paris, Brussels, London,
Moscow, Seoul, Tokyo and Beijing, the U.S. secretary of state will
mainly focus on the NATO enlargement plan, which has been strongly
opposed by Russia who thought the plan would threaten its security.
</P>
<P>
A "more structured relationship" will be sought with Russia,
leading to a possible "charter" or "statute" in which Russia would
have a greater political say in the process and would be more
involved in peace missions, said Dini.
</P>
<P>
The Western military alliance has proposed a charter with
Russia that envisages a joint council for intensive consultations
in an effort to eliminate Moscow's concerns about NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
NATO is expected to discuss admissions of new members, most
probably Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic, at a summit
scheduled in Madrid on July 7-8.
</P>
<P>
During her day-long visit to Rome, Albright also discussed with
Dini the relationship with Libya, Cuba, Iraq and Iran, which
Washington would like to see isolated, but they remained different
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Dini hoped that the hurdles which prevent the normalization of
relations between Libya and the world community can be gradually
cleared by an effort on Libya's part and a little understanding on
the West. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
