<HEADLINE> Philippine Military to Attack Muslim Extremists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine military is
preparing a major offensive against the Abu Sayyaf, a Muslim
extremist group, after the arrest of one of its ranking officers
Saturday, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Khadafi Janjalani, younger brother of Abu Sayyaf leader
Abdurajak Abubakar Janjalani, was arrested together with six other
Abu Sayyaf members Saturday in Cebu city in the southern Cebu
province, according to the Manila Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces chief of staff, Gen. Arnulfo Acedera, was
quoted as saying that with the capture of Khadafi Janjalani, the
military has gained better chances of capturing his elder brother.
</P>
<P>
Acedera said he had alerted the ground troops of the Armed
Forces to do extensive monitoring of the activities of the Abu
Sayyaf in several areas in Mindanao island.
</P>
<P>
He said the Abu Sayyaf has been giving the government problems
in its campaign to end violence in Mindanao through peaceful
means.
</P>
<P>
According to Acedera, with its membership diminishing to about
300, the Abu Sayyaf is trying desperately to regain its influence
in the southern Philippines by terrorizing civilians and attacking
religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
A 5 million peso (190,000 U.S. dollars) reward has been offered
for the arrest of elder Janjalani, considered the No.1 most wanted
criminal in the country.
</P>
<P>
The military said he was responsible for the death of hundreds
of civilians at the Ipil massacre in 1995 and the killing of Sulu
provincial bishop Benjamin de Jesus last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
