<HEADLINE> Some 400 People Seek 57 Official Posts in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Almost 400 people have applied
for 57 intermediate official vacancies in the Chinese capital
during the first two days of a 10-day application period.
</P>
<P>
Openings include those with the municipal government,
state-owned companies, publishing houses and universities. They
include bureau deputy directors and senior managers.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, the main hall of the Culture Palace for Working
People to the north of the Tiananmen Square - half the size of a
football court - bustled with people asking, consulting, and
filling out applications, according to China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Three hundred people registered for the exams on the opening
day, with another 100 registering the second day.
</P>
<P>
College graduates under 45 who have been division chiefs for
more than three years or vice-division chiefs for more than five
years are eligible for the recruitment drive. The age limit can be
extended to 50 for exceptional candidates.
</P>
<P>
"Recruitment through open exams offers a wider range of choice
for those capable," Zhao Xiaoling, deputy division chief of
personnel of the Beijing Statistic Bureau said.
</P>
<P>
The candidates will take writing and oral exams covering common
knowledge and specialties.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to women, ethnic minority and non-Party
member candidates over others with the same qualification.
</P>
<P>
Five bureau deputy directors were chosen this way in Beijing
last year. That was the first time since 1949 that the capital
adopted an open exam approach in recruiting intermediate-ranking
officials, an earlier report said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 30 provinces, municipalities and automonous regions
across the country, 25 have adopted the new methods.
</P>
<P>
The other five provinces are expected to follow suit when they
finish restructuring their provincial governments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
