<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Enterprises Inspection Strengthened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The State Administration for
Industry and Commerce (SAIC) will keep a sharper eye on corporate
activities than ever before, thanks to new regulations on annual
enterprise inspection in effect since last month.
</P>
<P>
The annual enterprise inspection is a major way for central and
local industry and commerce administrations to determine whether
an enterprise has followed the regulations and earned the right to
keep its business, said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The regulations require that every year from January to April,
all enterprises must report the prior year's major activities to
the administrations for industry and commerce.
</P>
<P>
Pan Haimin, head of the enterprise supervision division under
the SAIC, said the old regulations, first implemented in 1993, had
played an effective role but needed to be rectified.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations include revisions which will improve
enterprise management and help creat a fair business climate, Pan
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that this year the SAIC will cancel business licenses
for unqualified enterprises and for enterprises that have not
taken part in the annual inspection in the same year.
</P>
<P>
Under the former and less stringent regulations, both types of
enterprises would probably have kept their licenses.
</P>
<P>
Last year, about ten percent of all domestic enterprises did
not join in the annual inspection, Pan said.
</P>
<P>
This year the SAIC will, for the first time, distinguish
between two grades of qualified enterprises - Grade A and grade
B. Enterprises labelled grade B because of minor violations, will
be prohibited from opening new branches, investing overseas and
expanding operations, Pan said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the new regulations also apply to enterprises'
subsidiaries, whether independent or not, rather than formerly
only to independent enterprises.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to See Stagnant Wool Import </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 17 (Xinhua) -- China's wool imports will
remain below the level of a few years ago and the decline is
expected to continue, despite falling wool prices on the world
market, said a trade official.
</P>
<P>
Wool imports will increase slightly this year because of
China's China's economic growth but will be well below the former
average of 240,000 to 250,000 tons a year, the official was quoted
as saying in today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
"Wool consumption is expected to increase as China enters the
second year of its Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), but the
factors restricting wool imports in the past year will not change
overnight," Luan Richeng, general manager of Chinatex Raw
Materials Import and Export Corp, was quoted.
</P>
<P>
China remains one of the largest wool importers in the world,
even though its wool imports decreased in 1996, said Luan.
</P>
<P>
China imported 198,000 tons of wool, worth 753 million US
dollars, during the January-November period of 1996, down 22.6
percent from the same period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Luan attributed the slump in the wool trade partly to a lack of
funds in most domestic wool-spinning enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, an increasing number of textile enterprises have
lost sales, resulting in an increase in the inventories of
finished woolen and worsted products.
</P>
<P>
The wool-spinning sector is unable to turn out the high
value-added products demanded by the market, but has a production
over-capacity for goods of poor quality, Luan said.
</P>
<P>
Another factor affecting China's wool imports is the drop in
textile and garment exports, Luan said.
</P>
<P>
Customs statistics indicate that exports of textiles and
garments decreased 3.8 percent to 30.68 billion US dollars during
the first 11 months of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Luan said that Chinatex, the largest wool trading company in
the country, imported 50,000 tons of wool last year, about one
quarter of the total imported by the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0200 </DOCNO>
