<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Electronics Users Peer into China's LCDs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The liquid crystal display
(LCD) industry, an obscure and negligible sector of China's
economy a decade ago, now fills more than half of the
international demand for the screens.
</P>
<P>
The displays are used widely in the manufacture of watches,
laptop computers, calculators, pagers and miniature television
sets, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
In 1988, 35,000 square meters of the displays were produced by
Chinese plants, with sales worth only 73.6 million yuan (about
8.87 million US dollars). In 1995, however, 65 producers
manufactured 455,000 square meters of displays generating sales of
1.65 billion yuan (about 198.7 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Output continued rising -- to an estimated 550,000 square
meters in 1996 with sales worth two billion yuan (about 240
million US dollars), said Liu Peizheng, secretary-general of the
China Optics and Optoelectronics Industry Association's LCD branch.
</P>
<P>
Three types of LCDs are produced in China: low-grade twisted
nematic LCDs (TN-LCD), high-grade super twisted nematic LCDs
(STN-LCD) and the most advanced, thin-film transistor LCDs
(TFT-LCD).
</P>
<P>
Most of the industry's 43 production lines turn out TN-LCDs,
which are "competitive around the world," Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 80 percent of the TN-LCDs produced -- equivalent
to half the global demand -- are exported, the English-language
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
NT-LCDs worth 115 million US dollars were exported in 1995. The
final 1996 figure is expected to reach 130 million US dollars --
12 times the 10.7 million in export sales earned in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Domestically, the industry supplies 80 percent of the LCD
market.
</P>
<P>
Although the production technology for high-grade STN-LCD
screens lags behind those in Japan and other developed countries,
China's LCD industry has completed six production lines for
high-grade screens and 10 more are either being built or planned.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Electronics Industry is determined to restrict
the overheated expansion of STN-LCD production capacity, according
to a ministry official.
</P>
<P>
Liu echoed the ministry's stand, pointing out that the STN-LCD
market is still too limited.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the industry should give priority to scaling up
production of TN-LCDs and developing thin-film TFT-LCD
technology.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
