<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ to Use New Method to Fight Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, February 17 (Xinhua) -- The Wellington Hospital
will employ a new weapon in the fight against cancer which offers
new hope to patients with certain types of tumors.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper "The Dominion" reported today that the
process, involving modifying a particular type of cell to
stimulate the immune system to fight tumor, is about to be tried
after three years of laboratory work.
</P>
<P>
The cells are dentritic cells, a highly specialized form of
blood cell.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted researcher David Ritchie as saying that
dentritic cell therapy is not a world breakthrough yet. But it
will be a significant contribution in the area of immunotherapy,
which is where most research effort is now concentrated.
</P>
<P>
"We believe we are the only ones in the world applying
dentritic cell therapy like this," he said.
</P>
<P>
The process involves removing dendritic cells from the patient
and growing them to relatively large numbers before stimulating
them with an antigen from the tumor.
</P>
<P>
The "armed" cells will then to replaced in the patient,
stimulating his or her immune system to fight their tumor, the
reports said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
