<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty-stricken Villagers Bid Farewell to Thatched Sheds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, February 17 (Xinhua) -- Villagers in a remote city in
northwestern China have benefited from the local government's
poverty-combatting drive, changing their thatched-roof cottages
for tile-roofed brick houses.
</P>
<P>
Tianshui city in Gansu province is in an outlying remote
mountainous area that has 2.8 million people, a number of whom are
badly in need. To help them the city government began a two-year
project to renovate and rebuild thatched cottages for the most
poverty-stricken.
</P>
<P>
More than 11,400 thatched cottages scattered about six counties
and districts under the city's jurisdiction have been renovated
and rebuilt, benefiting approximately 20,000 villagers.
</P>
<P>
The city government has tried every means possible to get
funds, and various government departments have gotten over 2.3
million yuan (285,000 US dollars) for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
The city set up special offices at the county and district
level to handle the renovation work and to see to it that all
villagers living in thatched-roof dwellings move to new housing.
</P>
<P>
Villagers who benefitted from the move expressed their
gratitude by setting up stone tablets in their villages inscribed
with the words "Never forget the Loving-kindness of the Party and
government." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
