<HEADLINE> Muster Wins Dubai Open Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DUBAI, February 16 (Xinhua) -- Second seed Thomas Muster of
Austria beat defending champion Goran Ivanisevic of Croatia in the
final to win the 1 million U.S. dollars Dubai Tennis Open.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian, currently ranked third in the world behind
Ivanisevic, who was top seed here, scored a 7-5, 7-6 (7-3) victory
in one hour, 41 minutes.
</P>
<P>
"I played extremely well from the back court and put pressure
on him when necessary. I'm delighted with the way I fought," said
Muster, adding his next goal is the French Open. He also promised
to return next year to defend his title.
</P>
<P>
The whole mathc remained delicately balanced with only one
break in the two sets. But Ivanisevic, who served very well, made
so many errors in vital moments that kept himself away from
defending the title.
</P>
<P>
Muster, playing mostly from the baseline, looked more steady
and aggresive. He fond his first and last break in Ivanisevic's
fifth game.
</P>
<P>
In the first set, when Ivcanisevic makde a disasterous double
fault, Muster took advanctage of Ivanisevic's error and claimed a
6-5 lead. He consolidated the lead after holding his last game to
take a 7-5 win.
</P>
<P>
In the second, Ivanisevic and Muster raised their play to
extraordinary heights. Both players went for the most difficult of
winners, rallying for many strokes on some points on the hard
court.
</P>
<P>
With the set tied at 6-6, Muster raced to a 4-0 lead in the
tiebreaker as Ivanisevic's game was plagued by errors. Though the
defending champion battled back to 6-3, Muster ended the match
with an overhead smash.
</P>
<P>
Ivanisevic was downhearted after playing so well and only
managing to finish runner-up. "It was my best I have played for a
long time. I had many opportunities to break but I put all them
off," Ivanisevic said. Ednitem

nnnn
</P>
