<HEADLINE> U.S. Secretary of State Arrives in Bonn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright arrived Sunday evening in Bonn on the second leg of a
10-day tour that will take her to nine capitals in Europe and
Asia.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who is on her first tour abroad since she was sworn
in last month, is scheduled to meet with German Foreign Minister
Klaus Kinkel and Chancellor Helmut Kohl on Monday to discuss NATO
expansion, the Middle East peace process, the former Yugoslavia as
well as the U.S.-German differences on the controversial
Scientology sect.
</P>
<P>
Before flying to Bonn, she had met Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi, Defense Minister Beniamino Andreatta and Foreign
Minister Lamberto Dini. The main topic was NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
She told a press conference after the meetings in Rome that it
was not NATO's aim to oppose Russia. Russian opposition to the
proposed enlargement belonged to an outdated mentality.
</P>
<P>
Albright also made clear that Washington insisted on holding
NATO's South Command in Naples in opposition to French suggestions
that the post be transferred to Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
