<DOCNO> XIE19970217.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serbs Partly Satisfied with Ruling on Brcko </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, February 16 (Xinhua) -- The Bosnian Serb ruling
party, the Serbian Democratic Party (SDS), said Sunday it was
partly satisfied with the decision on Brcko made by international
arbiter Robert Owen since it provided only a temporary solution.
</P>
<P>
SDS's acting President Aleksa Buha, told reporters in Pale, the
Serb administrative center, that the uncertainty would continue
over the next year since the decision on the fate of the town was
put off until next year.
</P>
<P>
Roberts Owen, chairman of a three-member arbitration panel,
announced in Rome on Friday that the volatile town would be put
under international supervision pending a final decision in March
1998.
</P>
<P>
Brcko, claimed both by the Serb republic and the Muslim-Croat
federation, is situated on a land corridor in northeastern Bosnia
linking eastern and western parts of Serb-controlled territory,
thus vitally important to the Serb authority. Serb leaders had
threatened to resume war if the town, which is now under Serb
control, was not ruled in their favor.
</P>
<P>
But Buha, who is also the Serb foreign minister, said the
essential facts in the international decision were respect for the
strategic interest of the Serbs to remain the town within
Republika Srpska and no changes in demarcation lines.
</P>
<P>
This latest decision also envisaged a whole series of
additional measures stemming from the obligations which Republika
Srpska undertook in line with the Dayton accords, especially in
connection with freedom of movement and the right of refugees to
return home, Tanjug news agency quoted Buha as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to Owen, a supervisor would be assigned to work in
Brcko, ensuring full freedom of movement, overseeing the return of
Muslim-Croat refugees and implementing an economic revitalization
program for the Brcko area.
</P>
<P>
Buha said the implementation of the decision would be worked
out in detail at the conference in Vienna in early March. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
